PROFESSOR: But today, we'll
start with the customer

00:00:26.580 --> 00:00:31.320
information one, which I
really will admit that probably

00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:33.660
some of you folks know
more about this than I

00:00:33.660 --> 00:00:35.100
do at this point.

00:00:35.100 --> 00:00:36.930
But what I'm going
to do is cover

00:00:36.930 --> 00:00:38.580
the trends that
have been happening

00:00:38.580 --> 00:00:40.050
in the last couple of years.

00:00:40.050 --> 00:00:44.160
And then I'd like to get into
a discussion, towards the end,

00:00:44.160 --> 00:00:46.140
about where we should go.

00:00:46.140 --> 00:00:50.030
Because where we're starting
to do some research on this.

00:00:50.030 --> 00:00:54.000
Apar, who's usually
in the class, who's

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:56.400
doing some stuff here.

00:00:56.400 --> 00:01:01.170
And we can talk a little
bit more about this.

00:01:01.170 --> 00:01:06.600
This is the outline essentially
just saying where we've been

00:01:06.600 --> 00:01:11.040
and where we're going and
some ideas, essentially--

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:14.400
both my personal
ones and others'.

00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:17.280
This is actually a
lecture that started --

00:01:17.280 --> 00:01:21.270
The first version of this
was done by Nigel Wilson.

00:01:21.270 --> 00:01:23.810
So I gotta give him a
lot of credit for this.

00:01:23.810 --> 00:01:27.120
And then we've evolved
it, as it went,

00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:30.550
over the last several years.

00:01:30.550 --> 00:01:37.740
So this is a spectrum of
components of customer

00:01:37.740 --> 00:01:41.010
information-- or characteristics
of customer information,

00:01:41.010 --> 00:01:42.720
really--

00:01:42.720 --> 00:01:48.270
and how it's evolved from what
transit agencies are providing

00:01:48.270 --> 00:01:51.510
to their customers.

00:01:51.510 --> 00:01:55.170
On the left is what
was the old stuff.

00:01:55.170 --> 00:01:58.800
On the right is
where it's going.

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:02.140
And it's not all there yet.

00:02:02.140 --> 00:02:07.650
But generally, things have
been moving, and fairly quickly

00:02:07.650 --> 00:02:11.100
in the last couple of
years, from an operator

00:02:11.100 --> 00:02:12.960
view to a customer view.

00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:15.360
Operators used to
just tell people

00:02:15.360 --> 00:02:25.769
what their schedule was and
barely where the trains were.

00:02:25.769 --> 00:02:27.060
There were some maps out there.

00:02:27.060 --> 00:02:30.860
But way-finding
was very, very bad.

00:02:30.860 --> 00:02:34.830
And so, essentially, you
have to pick up these pieces

00:02:34.830 --> 00:02:36.870
of paper, which were static.

00:02:36.870 --> 00:02:42.270
And now it's moving to a more
dynamic real time perspective.

00:02:42.270 --> 00:02:47.380
Everything was always pre-trip
or pre-planning your trip.

00:02:47.380 --> 00:02:50.550
And now, there's some
indication that things

00:02:50.550 --> 00:02:52.694
are getting more en route.

00:02:52.694 --> 00:02:55.110
You have these real time apps
that we'll talk a little bit

00:02:55.110 --> 00:02:57.570
about.

00:02:57.570 --> 00:03:01.230
The last two are the ones that
probably haven't moved quite as

00:03:01.230 --> 00:03:03.840
fast as some would have hoped.

00:03:06.374 --> 00:03:08.040
I think most of the
customer information

00:03:08.040 --> 00:03:13.370
that's out there still treats
everyone as a generic customer.

00:03:13.370 --> 00:03:15.750
It doesn't really see
your particular needs,

00:03:15.750 --> 00:03:18.420
although there are things
like service alerts

00:03:18.420 --> 00:03:20.820
that you sign up for
very specific routes

00:03:20.820 --> 00:03:22.050
and things like that.

00:03:22.050 --> 00:03:27.030
But there's not too
much specific to you.

00:03:27.030 --> 00:03:32.280
And then, generally,
you've got to look still

00:03:32.280 --> 00:03:35.520
for the information and
pull it up yourself.

00:03:35.520 --> 00:03:41.190
It's not coming to you without
you taking any action, in most

00:03:41.190 --> 00:03:43.020
of these apps, although
some of the apps

00:03:43.020 --> 00:03:46.820
are starting to move that way.

00:03:46.820 --> 00:03:49.249
So, yeah.

00:03:49.249 --> 00:03:51.290
AUDIENCE: The active
systems and passive systems,

00:03:51.290 --> 00:03:53.918
is that supposed to be
the other way around?

00:03:53.918 --> 00:03:55.370
What's with the active part?

00:03:55.370 --> 00:03:59.270
PROFESSOR: The active part
is from the perspective

00:03:59.270 --> 00:03:59.960
of the customer.

00:03:59.960 --> 00:04:01.910
The customer has to
actively seek out

00:04:01.910 --> 00:04:04.100
the information as
opposed to it coming

00:04:04.100 --> 00:04:06.122
to him without doing anything.

00:04:06.122 --> 00:04:09.070
OK.

00:04:09.070 --> 00:04:09.570
Yeah.

00:04:09.570 --> 00:04:13.200
And anybody, you can
interrupt, as well.

00:04:13.200 --> 00:04:16.620
I like the give and take.

00:04:16.620 --> 00:04:22.120
It's the technologies that allow
these things to include things

00:04:22.120 --> 00:04:25.990
that you've pretty much
talked about here, probably

00:04:25.990 --> 00:04:28.570
already, automatic
vehicle location

00:04:28.570 --> 00:04:31.330
systems, automatic
scheduling systems,

00:04:31.330 --> 00:04:37.780
so that the whole data of the
mission of the transit agency

00:04:37.780 --> 00:04:41.030
is now in digital form.

00:04:41.030 --> 00:04:45.990
And more generally, is available
to the public through what

00:04:45.990 --> 00:04:50.770
most [INAUDIBLE] used to call
the Google Transit Data Feed.

00:04:50.770 --> 00:04:53.830
And now it's the General
Transit Data Feed.

00:04:53.830 --> 00:04:58.050
Because, basically, everybody
adopted what Google started.

00:04:58.050 --> 00:05:01.570
And it provides
universal formats

00:05:01.570 --> 00:05:04.360
that all the transit
agencies have basically

00:05:04.360 --> 00:05:07.930
converted their data to.

00:05:07.930 --> 00:05:11.470
GPS and Wi-Fi cell phones.

00:05:11.470 --> 00:05:14.530
GPS is used on the vehicles,
generally, sometimes

00:05:14.530 --> 00:05:16.900
in the cell phones.

00:05:16.900 --> 00:05:19.780
But essentially,
provides your location.

00:05:19.780 --> 00:05:22.780
And this is where the
customer specific stuff

00:05:22.780 --> 00:05:23.590
has gotten better.

00:05:23.590 --> 00:05:26.590
Because that technology
has allowed it.

00:05:26.590 --> 00:05:30.280
If you didn't have a
phone that told everybody

00:05:30.280 --> 00:05:35.650
where you were you wouldn't
be able to get information

00:05:35.650 --> 00:05:38.860
as good as you do now.

00:05:38.860 --> 00:05:43.900
AFC provides a database
on your trip-making.

00:05:43.900 --> 00:05:46.940
And that's important
for two reasons.

00:05:46.940 --> 00:05:53.410
One, it allows the agency to
know where people are traveling

00:05:53.410 --> 00:05:56.110
much better than they used to.

00:05:56.110 --> 00:06:01.030
And it also allows
them, if they so desire,

00:06:01.030 --> 00:06:05.620
to start to develop stuff for
you based on your history.

00:06:05.620 --> 00:06:09.190
And this is a little
bit controversial.

00:06:09.190 --> 00:06:11.320
We still have a
lot of discussions

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:15.880
with transit agencies about
the privacy of the data

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:20.770
and tracking you through
there and your taps.

00:06:20.770 --> 00:06:26.920
But frankly, all the commercial
people were doing this.

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:31.270
And I think, the customers
come to expect it.

00:06:31.270 --> 00:06:36.400
And the agencies have
to get over this hump,

00:06:36.400 --> 00:06:40.300
do a privacy policy
that says, we're

00:06:40.300 --> 00:06:42.320
going to use this
data in these ways.

00:06:42.320 --> 00:06:45.220
And we're going to
give people information

00:06:45.220 --> 00:06:47.770
based on their previous travel.

00:06:47.770 --> 00:06:50.870
I don't think too many
people have done that yet,

00:06:50.870 --> 00:06:52.120
but they're thinking about it.

00:06:52.120 --> 00:06:55.540
And unfortunately, sometimes
the government lawyers

00:06:55.540 --> 00:06:59.020
are more obstinate
about doing things

00:06:59.020 --> 00:07:04.420
like this than the private
sector lawyers who generally--

00:07:04.420 --> 00:07:11.620
my biased observation
is, the private lawyers

00:07:11.620 --> 00:07:13.630
finds a way to do with
the company management

00:07:13.630 --> 00:07:14.350
wants them to do.

00:07:14.350 --> 00:07:17.699
The government
lawyers finds a way

00:07:17.699 --> 00:07:19.240
to tell management
they can't do what

00:07:19.240 --> 00:07:21.250
they want to do, in many cases.

00:07:21.250 --> 00:07:26.660
And it's unfortunate
from that perspective.

00:07:26.660 --> 00:07:31.960
And then, obviously, wireless
communications and the apps

00:07:31.960 --> 00:07:34.520
that have been developed.

00:07:34.520 --> 00:07:37.460
So before Google
Transit, and this

00:07:37.460 --> 00:07:40.340
is probably ancient
in your eyes,

00:07:40.340 --> 00:07:42.950
but there used to
be a bunch of--

00:07:42.950 --> 00:07:46.920
not a bunch-- about
three or four or five--

00:07:46.920 --> 00:07:51.870
software companies worldwide
who did these things.

00:07:51.870 --> 00:07:56.580
And they were doing it
with really old technology.

00:07:56.580 --> 00:07:59.220
And they were mainframe systems.

00:07:59.220 --> 00:08:01.620
And they collected
literally, $1 million

00:08:01.620 --> 00:08:03.540
for each Transit Authority.

00:08:03.540 --> 00:08:11.400
And it was funny to see Google
do this for free, essentially.

00:08:11.400 --> 00:08:14.610
Because these companies almost--

00:08:14.610 --> 00:08:21.900
a lot of them just died
because of the competition.

00:08:21.900 --> 00:08:26.460
So when they first did
this, we were all amazed.

00:08:26.460 --> 00:08:29.040
Because a lot of the
big transit authorities

00:08:29.040 --> 00:08:32.270
had invested lots
and lots of money

00:08:32.270 --> 00:08:33.659
to the majority of planners.

00:08:33.659 --> 00:08:38.200
And they involved a tremendous
amount of data preparation

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:42.270
and a lot of customization
for each city.

00:08:42.270 --> 00:08:48.750
And this was a breakthrough
that nobody ever saw.

00:08:48.750 --> 00:08:50.730
Nobody quite
understood why Google

00:08:50.730 --> 00:08:53.460
was doing it at the time.

00:08:53.460 --> 00:08:56.250
But it was welcomed.

00:08:56.250 --> 00:09:01.200
And there's some funny stories
about how it was then adapted.

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:03.620
Because a lot of the big
transit authorities already

00:09:03.620 --> 00:09:05.370
had these trip planners
that they invested

00:09:05.370 --> 00:09:07.190
these millions of dollars on.

00:09:07.190 --> 00:09:11.490
And they were loathe
to give them up.

00:09:11.490 --> 00:09:15.450
And they were loathe to then
change the input to the Google

00:09:15.450 --> 00:09:17.130
Trip input.

00:09:17.130 --> 00:09:19.680
Because all the formats
of these other things

00:09:19.680 --> 00:09:21.180
were all proprietary.

00:09:21.180 --> 00:09:24.030
And they basically had
to do a lot of work

00:09:24.030 --> 00:09:26.680
to get it into Google transit.

00:09:26.680 --> 00:09:31.420
But they got embarrassed
into it by students, students

00:09:31.420 --> 00:09:34.000
even on the high
school level, who

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:37.600
really took their
towns' schedules

00:09:37.600 --> 00:09:40.680
and put them into
Google transit.

00:09:40.680 --> 00:09:45.640
And this was done in
city after city, really.

00:09:45.640 --> 00:09:49.480
In some cases, in big
cities, to show them up.

00:09:49.480 --> 00:09:51.520
And other cases,
in little cities,

00:09:51.520 --> 00:09:54.040
because they just didn't
have the staff to do it.

00:09:54.040 --> 00:09:58.302
So it was a great development.

00:09:58.302 --> 00:10:02.000
You've seen the apps that--

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:06.050
next vehicle arrival
times, but on your phone,

00:10:06.050 --> 00:10:08.830
which you all probably use.

00:10:08.830 --> 00:10:10.554
There's many new apps.

00:10:10.554 --> 00:10:11.470
Some of them are good.

00:10:11.470 --> 00:10:12.636
Some of them aren't so good.

00:10:16.270 --> 00:10:17.640
Give the Google data out.

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:21.010
And have other people
write the apps.

00:10:21.010 --> 00:10:24.910
That was the chosen
path, because they

00:10:24.910 --> 00:10:29.140
realize they couldn't do it as
quickly as private people could

00:10:29.140 --> 00:10:30.760
do it.

00:10:30.760 --> 00:10:36.400
And they, essentially,
let this go.

00:10:36.400 --> 00:10:40.780
My criticism of this approach--

00:10:40.780 --> 00:10:45.130
I think in Boston we had
between 35 and 45 transit

00:10:45.130 --> 00:10:49.570
apps, none of which
were well supported

00:10:49.570 --> 00:10:51.850
for about two or three years.

00:10:51.850 --> 00:10:53.890
Nobody quite knew.

00:10:53.890 --> 00:10:55.985
The people who really cared--

00:10:55.985 --> 00:10:58.360
there was a little bit of
word-of-mouth that went around.

00:10:58.360 --> 00:11:02.030
There was the rating systems
online and things like that.

00:11:02.030 --> 00:11:06.310
But when you ask around, there
was at least a half dozen

00:11:06.310 --> 00:11:09.280
that were being used
and nobody quite

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:11.920
knew whether they
were good or not.

00:11:11.920 --> 00:11:15.190
And basically, everybody had a
different standard with respect

00:11:15.190 --> 00:11:18.850
to whether they would use them.

00:11:18.850 --> 00:11:23.570
And so, recently,
they've changed.

00:11:23.570 --> 00:11:26.590
They've started to endorse apps.

00:11:26.590 --> 00:11:33.010
The MBTA this year endorsed
Transit as their app.

00:11:33.010 --> 00:11:36.160
In a lot of cities, City
Mapper has been become

00:11:36.160 --> 00:11:39.020
the standard for most people.

00:11:39.020 --> 00:11:42.400
And so, there's
two or three that

00:11:42.400 --> 00:11:48.610
are reasonably good both in the
design and in the information.

00:11:48.610 --> 00:11:53.230
But I'll talk about the good
and the bad of these in a second

00:11:53.230 --> 00:11:56.571
here So I've put three--

00:11:56.571 --> 00:11:57.070
yeah.

00:11:57.070 --> 00:11:58.870
Go ahead.

