So it becomes other
mobility services as well as

00:15:58.790 --> 00:15:59.720
public transit.

00:15:59.720 --> 00:16:00.357
Yeah.

00:16:00.357 --> 00:16:03.505
AUDIENCE: I suspected that
when those Uber services

00:16:03.505 --> 00:16:07.280
TNCs started popping
up on the transit apps,

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:10.055
I suspected that
they might be paying

00:16:10.055 --> 00:16:11.760
those apps to have that option.

00:16:11.760 --> 00:16:16.100
Because those options didn't
exist until not too long ago.

00:16:16.100 --> 00:16:18.830
And suddenly, you
see this option.

00:16:18.830 --> 00:16:21.100
Is there any truth to that?

00:16:21.100 --> 00:16:23.320
PROFESSOR: Well, the
first one that tried

00:16:23.320 --> 00:16:24.830
is a thing that's extinct now.

00:16:24.830 --> 00:16:26.350
It's called RideScout.

00:16:26.350 --> 00:16:28.910
RideScout was the first
one who tried to put

00:16:28.910 --> 00:16:30.410
all these things together.

00:16:30.410 --> 00:16:34.790
And they actually got resistance
at first from Uber and Lyft.

00:16:34.790 --> 00:16:38.540
Because at the
beginning, Uber and Lyft

00:16:38.540 --> 00:16:42.260
felt like they had all the
demand that they could handle.

00:16:42.260 --> 00:16:45.380
And they wanted people
to go to their app.

00:16:45.380 --> 00:16:47.660
They didn't want to pay them.

00:16:47.660 --> 00:16:50.930
Now, I don't know.

00:16:50.930 --> 00:16:54.250
This Transit app clearly has it.

00:16:54.250 --> 00:16:56.630
And a lot of the other ones--

00:16:56.630 --> 00:16:58.700
CityMapper also does.

00:16:58.700 --> 00:17:00.500
Yeah.

00:17:00.500 --> 00:17:03.200
So I think they are paying them.

00:17:03.200 --> 00:17:08.510
But that's the maturity
of the TNCs as well.

00:17:08.510 --> 00:17:12.290
Because they're trying to get as
much market share as they can.

00:17:12.290 --> 00:17:14.790
And also because Uber
has so much money,

00:17:14.790 --> 00:17:17.560
they just throw it at
everything in order

00:17:17.560 --> 00:17:19.530
to get as much as they want.

00:17:19.530 --> 00:17:23.089
Don't worry, I'll make other
editorial comments about Uber

00:17:23.089 --> 00:17:23.869
as we go along.

00:17:23.869 --> 00:17:26.099
[LAUGHING]

00:17:26.099 --> 00:17:28.130
All right.

00:17:28.130 --> 00:17:35.330
So this is the possibilities.

00:17:35.330 --> 00:17:40.700
And the last is, can we attract
more customers using these?

00:17:40.700 --> 00:17:44.470
And that's the open question.

00:17:44.470 --> 00:17:48.090
There's some
indication that we can.

00:17:48.090 --> 00:17:50.820
I think, from a
research side, we

00:17:50.820 --> 00:17:56.550
want to do more testing of
pilot projects to see if we can.

00:17:56.550 --> 00:18:01.050
I believe the second
point is really important.

00:18:01.050 --> 00:18:05.760
We need not only information,
but integrated payment

00:18:05.760 --> 00:18:12.420
mechanisms on the phone so
that you don't have a separate

00:18:12.420 --> 00:18:15.510
barrier to taking
transit, which is,

00:18:15.510 --> 00:18:18.240
you gotta get a fare card or you
gotta put money in the fare box

00:18:18.240 --> 00:18:19.680
or you gotta--

00:18:19.680 --> 00:18:23.460
there's some transaction
cost with the way

00:18:23.460 --> 00:18:25.530
fares are in Transit.

00:18:25.530 --> 00:18:28.950
If it's all on the phone
and it's all together,

00:18:28.950 --> 00:18:32.280
it really makes it a
lot easier, I think.

00:18:32.280 --> 00:18:39.690
And so, feel that if you put
the two together, you get more.

00:18:39.690 --> 00:18:42.270
There aren't too many
people that have done that.

00:18:42.270 --> 00:18:47.970
Chicago has the Ventra system
that does, to a large degree,

00:18:47.970 --> 00:18:50.100
do this.

00:18:50.100 --> 00:18:53.610
They're only doing it for
transit systems in Chicago.

00:18:53.610 --> 00:18:54.870
They're doing it for the CTA.

00:18:54.870 --> 00:18:57.000
But you can buy a
metro ticket now.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:00.480
So it's actually multi
operator in the Chicago area.

00:19:00.480 --> 00:19:01.910
It's the commuter rail.

00:19:01.910 --> 00:19:04.620
And you can also
use it for PACE.

00:19:04.620 --> 00:19:08.880
So it's an account
based system on an app.

00:19:08.880 --> 00:19:12.660
And then you can get information
in terms of the services

00:19:12.660 --> 00:19:13.920
as well.

00:19:13.920 --> 00:19:16.650
So it's getting there.

00:19:16.650 --> 00:19:18.660
There aren't too many systems.

00:19:18.660 --> 00:19:23.335
Dallas uses information app
that includes payment as well--

00:19:23.335 --> 00:19:24.490
unlimited.

00:19:24.490 --> 00:19:27.460
There's a few of them out there.

00:19:27.460 --> 00:19:30.610
London's got the payment.

00:19:30.610 --> 00:19:34.070
And now they're doing the
app for the information.

00:19:34.070 --> 00:19:39.600
So they were ahead in terms of
different payment mechanisms.

00:19:43.460 --> 00:19:45.040
So it's getting there.

00:19:45.040 --> 00:19:48.340
The question really
is, what do you need

00:19:48.340 --> 00:19:50.250
to get people's eyes on it?

00:19:50.250 --> 00:19:56.590
And right now, I believe
it's mostly word-of-mouth.

00:19:56.590 --> 00:20:00.599
Those transit agencies spend
very, very little on marketing.

00:20:00.599 --> 00:20:02.640
They used to do advertising
and things like that.

00:20:02.640 --> 00:20:07.090
All that stuff's gone by
the board with the operating

00:20:07.090 --> 00:20:08.710
resource constraints
they've had.

00:20:08.710 --> 00:20:13.880
So it's like a lot of things.

00:20:13.880 --> 00:20:15.640
There's all these
new things out there.

00:20:15.640 --> 00:20:18.340
But how do you get people
to even look at it.

00:20:18.340 --> 00:20:23.050
And that's a big question
that the big companies

00:20:23.050 --> 00:20:24.160
know how to do.

00:20:24.160 --> 00:20:27.520
The transit agencies clearly
haven't figured that out yet.

00:20:31.884 --> 00:20:32.800
goes a little further.

00:20:35.970 --> 00:20:41.070
So this is an idea
that when London

00:20:41.070 --> 00:20:44.820
was talking about integrated
payment on a phone

00:20:44.820 --> 00:20:48.330
and using your credit
card account to do it.

00:20:48.330 --> 00:20:50.490
George Kocher said,
yeah, don't stop there.

00:20:50.490 --> 00:20:53.280
Do all the information, as well.

00:20:53.280 --> 00:20:59.910
And you can essentially just
have the whole transaction

00:20:59.910 --> 00:21:02.910
with public transit and,
potentially, other mobility

00:21:02.910 --> 00:21:05.220
services right in your pocket.

00:21:05.220 --> 00:21:09.000
The public sector
has been wary of is

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:14.460
this whole idea of tracking
your movements and keeping it.

00:21:14.460 --> 00:21:18.750
And that has been
a difficult thing

00:21:18.750 --> 00:21:20.250
to get over even
in the research.

00:21:20.250 --> 00:21:22.680
We've tried to do
little pilot projects.

00:21:22.680 --> 00:21:27.300
And the amount of
bureaucracy you

00:21:27.300 --> 00:21:32.100
have to go through in order to
essentially ask people if we

00:21:32.100 --> 00:21:34.320
can track their movements--

00:21:34.320 --> 00:21:36.030
which, by the way,
when you do ask them,

00:21:36.030 --> 00:21:38.280
and you tell them what you're
doing it for, especially

00:21:38.280 --> 00:21:47.910
for transit, over 50% is our
experience actually agree.

00:21:47.910 --> 00:21:54.240
So it's a large sample of
the users agree to this.

00:21:54.240 --> 00:21:56.660
Because, essentially,
they see the value

00:21:56.660 --> 00:22:00.040
at some of the information
that's coming back.

00:22:00.040 --> 00:22:04.200
So the challenges that are left.

00:22:04.200 --> 00:22:07.680
There's still some
agencies, when

00:22:07.680 --> 00:22:09.300
you go from city
to city, that don't

00:22:09.300 --> 00:22:11.910
have a lot of good
real time information.

00:22:11.910 --> 00:22:14.940
So the apps don't
work very well.

00:22:14.940 --> 00:22:21.030
And for the life of me, it's
just a matter of inertia,

00:22:21.030 --> 00:22:24.150
I believe, in these places.

00:22:24.150 --> 00:22:26.220
Although in some
cases, they just

00:22:26.220 --> 00:22:29.340
don't have the technology staff.

00:22:29.340 --> 00:22:33.060
I mean, they're below
water all the time,

00:22:33.060 --> 00:22:36.330
in terms of the projects
they have on technology.

00:22:36.330 --> 00:22:40.020
And this is not their
highest priority.

00:22:40.020 --> 00:22:42.720
But we still have a lot
of cities that aren't

00:22:42.720 --> 00:22:44.197
releasing the real time data.

00:22:44.197 --> 00:22:45.780
So some of these
apps just don't work.

00:22:50.028 --> 00:22:53.950
The standard format
for the schedule data

00:22:53.950 --> 00:22:58.870
is pretty much established--
the general transit data feed.

00:22:58.870 --> 00:23:04.270
But the GTA [? available ?] time
is not that well established.

00:23:04.270 --> 00:23:10.180
And most cities that provide
real time data to the public

00:23:10.180 --> 00:23:11.830
do it this way.

00:23:11.830 --> 00:23:14.200
But they sometimes do
it in a different way.

00:23:14.200 --> 00:23:16.930
So actually, MBTA
has two formats.

00:23:16.930 --> 00:23:21.820
And it turns out
that right now--

00:23:21.820 --> 00:23:24.370
the GTA vest format,
and you can correct me

00:23:24.370 --> 00:23:26.560
on this one, Gabrielle.

00:23:26.560 --> 00:23:30.070
But the GTA vest format
requires the developers

00:23:30.070 --> 00:23:34.660
to download all of the
data for all of the routes

00:23:34.660 --> 00:23:38.240
when they ask for it.

00:23:38.240 --> 00:23:40.240
It's setup for
somebody who wants

00:23:40.240 --> 00:23:46.810
to pull every route,
whereas in some cases,

00:23:46.810 --> 00:23:50.920
if you want to do this faster
and you want to do it smarter,

00:23:50.920 --> 00:23:53.290
you don't want to keep
pulling the whole system.

00:23:53.290 --> 00:23:56.050
Because you can't
do it fast enough.

00:23:56.050 --> 00:23:59.380
And I think this is something
we found when we were actually

00:23:59.380 --> 00:24:01.060
using it for a
different purpose--

00:24:01.060 --> 00:24:03.310
for an internal purpose.

00:24:03.310 --> 00:24:09.490
But we wanted to use their
separate API to their database

00:24:09.490 --> 00:24:12.570
where this data resides.

00:24:12.570 --> 00:24:14.190
Is that--

00:24:14.190 --> 00:24:17.450
AUDIENCE: It's mostly correct.

00:24:17.450 --> 00:24:25.070
One distinction [INAUDIBLE]
[? format ?] [INAUDIBLE] data

00:24:25.070 --> 00:24:32.370
[INAUDIBLE] agencies like the
[? MBTA ?] [INAUDIBLE] one

00:24:32.370 --> 00:24:36.390
example [INAUDIBLE] is the
waiting time for the Green

00:24:36.390 --> 00:24:37.790
Line.

00:24:37.790 --> 00:24:41.699
So they've developed a
custom API [INAUDIBLE]..

00:24:41.699 --> 00:24:42.740
PROFESSOR: Based on that.

00:24:45.570 --> 00:24:48.480
The biggest issue with
all of these apps,

00:24:48.480 --> 00:24:52.800
really, is they don't
work well in predicting

00:24:52.800 --> 00:24:56.280
when the bus is going
to arrive unless there's

00:24:56.280 --> 00:24:58.140
no traffic out there.

00:24:58.140 --> 00:25:04.380
So when there are generally good
conditions in terms of traffic,

00:25:04.380 --> 00:25:08.460
they're generally good at
predicting the arrival.

00:25:08.460 --> 00:25:11.490
When there's disruptions
and when there's

00:25:11.490 --> 00:25:14.970
any significant
level of congestion,

00:25:14.970 --> 00:25:20.400
they always underestimate the
time that you're going to wait.

00:25:20.400 --> 00:25:21.720
And you can see this.

00:25:21.720 --> 00:25:24.120
And people get very,
very frustrated

00:25:24.120 --> 00:25:26.100
when it says it's going
to arrive in 4 minutes,

00:25:26.100 --> 00:25:27.790
and it takes 8 or 9 minutes.

00:25:27.790 --> 00:25:28.500
Yeah.

00:25:28.500 --> 00:25:29.038
Yeah.

00:25:29.038 --> 00:25:32.014
AUDIENCE: Can you say something
about when the code shows

00:25:32.014 --> 00:25:35.250
the vehicle [INAUDIBLE]

00:25:35.250 --> 00:25:35.940
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:25:35.940 --> 00:25:38.400
Well, the Transit app does that.

00:25:38.400 --> 00:25:43.110
You can push it and see the
map and see where the bus is.

00:25:43.110 --> 00:25:45.240
And so, that helps.

00:25:45.240 --> 00:25:48.210
Because when you get
to know your route

00:25:48.210 --> 00:25:52.050
and you get to know how long
it generally takes when--

00:25:52.050 --> 00:25:55.590
I take the route 1
bus towards Harvard.

00:25:55.590 --> 00:25:56.895
So I look out over the bridge.

00:25:56.895 --> 00:26:00.000
And if the bridge is backed
up and it says 3 minutes,

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:04.260
I know it's really
about 8 to 10 minutes.

00:26:04.260 --> 00:26:05.220
So you're right.

00:26:05.220 --> 00:26:08.680
It does help when it does that.

00:26:08.680 --> 00:26:14.820
But frankly, for everyone,
that's another button.

00:26:14.820 --> 00:26:18.060
You have to scroll through
the map to see if it's there.

00:26:18.060 --> 00:26:19.770
The vehicles don't
always show up.

00:26:19.770 --> 00:26:23.010
Because that vehicle hadn't
been pulled in the last--

00:26:23.010 --> 00:26:26.710
whatever-- minutes or something.

00:26:26.710 --> 00:26:28.650
And there's a lag time.

00:26:28.650 --> 00:26:32.770
There's a lag time with
the update on this thing.

00:26:32.770 --> 00:26:34.800
There's a student in
electrical engineering

00:26:34.800 --> 00:26:39.420
who wants to do his master's
thesis on throwing out--

00:26:39.420 --> 00:26:41.040
most of these
predictions in Boston

00:26:41.040 --> 00:26:44.400
are based on the NextBus
black box algorithm.

00:26:44.400 --> 00:26:47.110
And we don't know
exactly what's in there.

00:26:47.110 --> 00:26:51.570
It's mostly based on historical
information about travel times

00:26:51.570 --> 00:26:52.530
on the route.

00:26:52.530 --> 00:26:54.450
So the way the algorithm
generally works

00:26:54.450 --> 00:26:58.230
is historical travel times
on the route by time-of-day.

00:26:58.230 --> 00:27:01.620
And then it puts in a little bit
of the last one or two buses.

00:27:01.620 --> 00:27:04.890
But we don't think it
puts in enough of that.

00:27:04.890 --> 00:27:09.690
So there is a student in
electrical engineering

00:27:09.690 --> 00:27:13.400
who wants to perhaps
do a master's program.

00:27:13.400 --> 00:27:19.320
Because he is very frustrated
at the MIT shuttle predictions,

00:27:19.320 --> 00:27:23.430
which are always
not very accurate.

00:27:23.430 --> 00:27:26.880
And he wants to throw out
the NextBus predictions

00:27:26.880 --> 00:27:29.800
and put in the
homegrown prediction.

00:27:29.800 --> 00:27:32.100
And so we'll see
how that works out.

00:27:32.100 --> 00:27:34.300
AUDIENCE: I guess, the
next level for these apps

00:27:34.300 --> 00:27:40.050
is to pull data from
Waze or some live data

00:27:40.050 --> 00:27:42.460
I think it's the big
problem which is how much

00:27:42.460 --> 00:27:45.795
longer it actually will take
the bus to get from A to B.

00:27:45.795 --> 00:27:49.050
And then there's the
advantage, thinking of Waze,

00:27:49.050 --> 00:27:51.530
of having that
they're linking a lot

00:27:51.530 --> 00:27:54.770
more vehicles and people
are transmitting this,

00:27:54.770 --> 00:27:59.060
well then integrate
expected Transit travel

00:27:59.060 --> 00:28:01.490
times and the actual
travel time on the road.

00:28:01.490 --> 00:28:02.650
We could integrate that.

00:28:02.650 --> 00:28:04.970
And it would be a
very powerful tool.

00:28:04.970 --> 00:28:05.760
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:28:05.760 --> 00:28:07.650
That's exactly what
he is going to do.

00:28:07.650 --> 00:28:12.890
He's going to use the
Google real time traffic.

00:28:12.890 --> 00:28:13.770
And then, so, yeah.

00:28:13.770 --> 00:28:16.755
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] when
you the [INAUDIBLE] transit

00:28:16.755 --> 00:28:18.030
[INAUDIBLE]

00:28:18.030 --> 00:28:19.560
PROFESSOR: It's using their--

00:28:19.560 --> 00:28:27.720
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:27.720 --> 00:28:30.630
PROFESSOR: I think
on Google Transit,

00:28:30.630 --> 00:28:34.040
there's a little indicator
whether it's real time or not

00:28:34.040 --> 00:28:35.000
real time.

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:39.530
And if that's bolded,
you know it's real time.

00:28:39.530 --> 00:28:41.540
And it's based on something.

00:28:41.540 --> 00:28:43.900
But again, those companies--

00:28:43.900 --> 00:28:45.740
it's just like NextBus.

00:28:45.740 --> 00:28:47.210
They have their own algorithm.

00:28:47.210 --> 00:28:49.730
And the question really is--

00:28:49.730 --> 00:28:51.830
I don't know who the
people in the traffic field

00:28:51.830 --> 00:28:55.100
are, whether they're looking
at these predictions.

00:28:55.100 --> 00:29:00.450
But I know if you look
at the Bluetooth signs

00:29:00.450 --> 00:29:04.120
on the traffic side,
there's a huge lag effect.

00:29:04.120 --> 00:29:09.780
So when traffic is building
up, you never get enough--

00:29:09.780 --> 00:29:11.940
the Bluetooth
prediction is too low.

00:29:11.940 --> 00:29:16.350
When traffic is coming down,
the Bluetooth projection

00:29:16.350 --> 00:29:17.850
is too high.

00:29:17.850 --> 00:29:20.940
And I look at this all
the time on the highways.

00:29:20.940 --> 00:29:23.980
Because I gotta go back
and forth to Cape Cod.

00:29:23.980 --> 00:29:30.030
And it's amazing to see, it
is better than the Transit

00:29:30.030 --> 00:29:31.500
predictions, I
can tell you that.

00:29:31.500 --> 00:29:33.333
The other issue with
the Transit predictions

00:29:33.333 --> 00:29:37.600
is they've got issues that
the Traffic doesn't have.

00:29:37.600 --> 00:29:40.470
They got dwell
time at the stops.

00:29:40.470 --> 00:29:44.610
And all it takes is one
wheelchair at Central Square

00:29:44.610 --> 00:29:48.870
to be loaded and that thing
is off by 2 or 3 minutes, just

00:29:48.870 --> 00:29:49.950
like that.

00:29:49.950 --> 00:29:53.400
Because it takes 2 or 3
minutes to load a wheelchair

00:29:53.400 --> 00:29:54.783
and secure the wheelchair.

00:29:57.510 --> 00:30:00.690
And then there's sometimes a
crowd coming out of the subway.

00:30:00.690 --> 00:30:05.280
And depending on the
driver, they wave

00:30:05.280 --> 00:30:08.580
on the people who they
think have passes.

00:30:08.580 --> 00:30:12.180
Other drivers, they tell
him to get on the back door.

00:30:12.180 --> 00:30:14.910
There's other drivers
say, no, you gotta--

00:30:14.910 --> 00:30:17.760
and then other drivers insist
you get behind the yellow line.

00:30:17.760 --> 00:30:20.160
And they'll sit there
at the stop for awhile.

00:30:20.160 --> 00:30:22.230
So there's all this
driver behavior,

00:30:22.230 --> 00:30:28.110
not to speak of the difference
in pulling in and out of stops

00:30:28.110 --> 00:30:32.130
among drivers, which you don't
have in the general traffic

00:30:32.130 --> 00:30:33.250
flow.

00:30:33.250 --> 00:30:34.950
So you got the
general traffic, you

00:30:34.950 --> 00:30:38.770
got the dwell times for
things like handicap vehicles.

00:30:38.770 --> 00:30:40.500
So it's a huge problem.

00:30:40.500 --> 00:30:45.620
It's not it's not a
simple algorithm to solve.

00:30:45.620 --> 00:30:50.410
It's one of those things that we
should be looking to do better.

00:30:54.631 --> 00:30:58.160
In major disruptions,
it really becomes

00:30:58.160 --> 00:31:02.160
an issue of how much
do you tell the public,

00:31:02.160 --> 00:31:03.620
let's do something else.

00:31:03.620 --> 00:31:06.690
This bus is not coming in any
reasonable amount of time.

00:31:06.690 --> 00:31:09.120
You can walk there a lot faster.

00:31:09.120 --> 00:31:12.800
And all the transit
agencies have been

00:31:12.800 --> 00:31:14.690
reluctant to figure that out.

00:31:14.690 --> 00:31:19.310
Although London is a lot
closer to thinking about,

00:31:19.310 --> 00:31:21.500
how do we tell people
about disruptions?

00:31:21.500 --> 00:31:27.110
And how much do we divert
them from their normal path?

00:31:27.110 --> 00:31:30.630
But there's not a lot
of real good research

00:31:30.630 --> 00:31:32.220
out there about how to do that.

00:31:34.890 --> 00:31:37.605
There is an issue with
the transit agencies

00:31:37.605 --> 00:31:39.730
that, again, it's because
it's a government agency.

00:31:39.730 --> 00:31:42.540
And this is probably more in
the US than anywhere else.

00:31:42.540 --> 00:31:46.230
But because of the Americans
with Disabilities Act,

00:31:46.230 --> 00:31:48.150
certain types of
information can't

00:31:48.150 --> 00:31:53.430
be given out to the public
by the transit agency

00:31:53.430 --> 00:31:55.740
unless it's fully accessible.

00:31:55.740 --> 00:32:00.070
And so, one of the reasons
we don't have more bus

00:32:00.070 --> 00:32:05.020
stop signs is because small bus
stop signs on small monitors

00:32:05.020 --> 00:32:07.960
are not accessible under
the terms of the Americans

00:32:07.960 --> 00:32:09.430
with Disabilities Act.

00:32:09.430 --> 00:32:14.820
So they have to spend a lot more
money doing accessible signs.

00:32:14.820 --> 00:32:20.692
And I would argue that
this is something that's--

00:32:20.692 --> 00:32:28.780
you can buy every disabled user
an accessible smartphone app

00:32:28.780 --> 00:32:32.620
built for that
cheaper than making

00:32:32.620 --> 00:32:36.370
every piece of
information accessible.

00:32:36.370 --> 00:32:42.270
But there's been no
movement on this.

00:32:42.270 --> 00:32:44.950
That's just an accepted fact.

00:32:44.950 --> 00:32:47.250
What they've done to get
around this a little bit is

00:32:47.250 --> 00:32:51.390
they say to the cities and
towns or somebody else--

00:32:51.390 --> 00:32:54.060
the federal transit agency
has their interpretation

00:32:54.060 --> 00:32:56.760
of an accessible
sign, and other people

00:32:56.760 --> 00:32:59.970
have different interpretations.

00:32:59.970 --> 00:33:03.240
So there is some
movement allowing.

00:33:03.240 --> 00:33:06.030
Like these private
transit screens

00:33:06.030 --> 00:33:11.220
you see, they have to be paid
for with non-federal money,

00:33:11.220 --> 00:33:12.960
essentially.

00:33:12.960 --> 00:33:15.990
And they're paid for,
usually, by private people

00:33:15.990 --> 00:33:19.710
or by the city under
some non-federal grant.

00:33:19.710 --> 00:33:20.210
Yeah.

00:33:20.210 --> 00:33:22.168
AUDIENCE: Do they have
to work with the NextBus

00:33:22.168 --> 00:33:24.540
commission [INAUDIBLE]

00:33:24.540 --> 00:33:26.490
PROFESSOR: Have to
have an audible thing

00:33:26.490 --> 00:33:29.250
or a Braille thing or
something like that.

00:33:29.250 --> 00:33:31.860
Yeah.

00:33:31.860 --> 00:33:35.760
And finally, this idea
of private ride sharing.

00:33:35.760 --> 00:33:39.990
And so, we have
all these systems

00:33:39.990 --> 00:33:43.980
and private operators that
are being incorporated here.

00:33:43.980 --> 00:33:48.750
But why not-- you can find me.

00:33:48.750 --> 00:33:56.310
If I want to give you a ride
from MIT to west Cambridge,

00:33:56.310 --> 00:33:58.170
why can't I get in that app?

00:33:58.170 --> 00:34:02.580
And then you could pay me
a few bucks for that ride.

00:34:02.580 --> 00:34:07.890
And there's a few people who
are developing mostly web

00:34:07.890 --> 00:34:09.900
applications right
now, but are starting

00:34:09.900 --> 00:34:12.780
to develop the phone
apps to do private ride

00:34:12.780 --> 00:34:15.630
sharing in this, as well.

00:34:15.630 --> 00:34:20.699
The Ubers of the world don't
like these things at all.

00:34:20.699 --> 00:34:24.179
And I don't really have any
good examples of people doing it

00:34:24.179 --> 00:34:25.409
on a wide-scale basis.

00:34:25.409 --> 00:34:28.170
But MIT is very
interested in doing this

00:34:28.170 --> 00:34:31.120
within their mobile app.

00:34:31.120 --> 00:34:31.620
So--

00:34:31.620 --> 00:34:32.245
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:34:32.245 --> 00:34:33.660
If I can give you an example.

00:34:33.660 --> 00:34:36.989
In Israel, where I come
from, Uber and Lyft

00:34:36.989 --> 00:34:38.389
have not been allowed in Israel.

00:34:38.389 --> 00:34:40.170
But they have allowed Google.

00:34:40.170 --> 00:34:43.739
And Google started privately
developing consultant areas

00:34:43.739 --> 00:34:46.550
where people use exactly
these services where

00:34:46.550 --> 00:34:48.480
if a private
individual says, I'm

00:34:48.480 --> 00:34:52.070
going from a suburb to the beach
right now at this time of day.

00:34:52.070 --> 00:34:55.396
If you want to join me and pay
me a few bucks for the ride.

00:34:55.396 --> 00:34:58.764
So Google actually has
started a pilot [INAUDIBLE]..

00:34:58.764 --> 00:34:59.430
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:34:59.430 --> 00:35:03.660
So I would argue
that this might not

00:35:03.660 --> 00:35:06.600
be the best thing for Transit
if we got everybody sharing

00:35:06.600 --> 00:35:07.530
rides all the time.

00:35:07.530 --> 00:35:10.000
But for the metropolitan
area and urban area,

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:11.360
it's probably a great thing.

00:35:11.360 --> 00:35:13.860
And it's better than having
Uber and Lyft drivers

00:35:13.860 --> 00:35:17.490
who, when they're not
full, running around empty.

00:35:17.490 --> 00:35:20.880
Because they're basically
a purposeful trip

00:35:20.880 --> 00:35:23.655
that's being made, as opposed
to just being a business.

00:35:28.040 --> 00:35:32.280
So these are potential
research questions.

00:35:32.280 --> 00:35:37.220
I think I've talked about
the arrival predictions.

00:35:37.220 --> 00:35:42.970
The second one is important.

00:35:42.970 --> 00:35:44.720
We do a lot of research
in the Transit lab

00:35:44.720 --> 00:35:49.020
about this using the
real time information,

00:35:49.020 --> 00:35:52.820
both from their vehicles
and from customers.

00:35:52.820 --> 00:35:56.570
Much less, thus far, from
customers in a real time

00:35:56.570 --> 00:35:58.070
framework.

00:35:58.070 --> 00:36:02.780
But if we have that kind
of information coming

00:36:02.780 --> 00:36:06.020
in all the time, how do
they make adjustments

00:36:06.020 --> 00:36:07.770
to the operating plan?

00:36:07.770 --> 00:36:15.960
So for example, the simplest one
of these is on ball game days.

00:36:15.960 --> 00:36:21.230
They store trains
outside of Kenmore Square

00:36:21.230 --> 00:36:23.420
and outside of
the Boston Garden.

00:36:23.420 --> 00:36:26.360
And then they only release
them when the crowd shows up

00:36:26.360 --> 00:36:27.740
on the platform.

00:36:27.740 --> 00:36:31.095
But it's still very low tech.

00:36:31.095 --> 00:36:32.390
There's a guy down there.

00:36:32.390 --> 00:36:33.490
And he says, send one in.

00:36:33.490 --> 00:36:37.290
[LAUGHING]

00:36:37.290 --> 00:36:41.100
But if you think about
that on a smaller scale,

00:36:41.100 --> 00:36:48.890
if a school gets out, and it's
on the Riverside line on the D

00:36:48.890 --> 00:36:54.950
branch, instead of on
the even headway at 3:48,

00:36:54.950 --> 00:36:57.110
you dispatch it a
little bit early.

00:36:57.110 --> 00:36:59.510
Because you knew the
school just got out.

00:36:59.510 --> 00:37:04.730
And you will pick up that
school load right away.

00:37:04.730 --> 00:37:07.910
And then the next
bus can pick up

00:37:07.910 --> 00:37:09.770
all the rest of the passengers.

00:37:09.770 --> 00:37:12.470
Or maybe they'll put two in
a row or something like that.

00:37:12.470 --> 00:37:17.000
This is good research.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:21.200
It's still in its infancy, I
would suggest, at this point.

00:37:24.160 --> 00:37:28.990
The travel behavior
question is paramount.

00:37:28.990 --> 00:37:33.740
And as I said, I don't know of
really good research on this.

00:37:33.740 --> 00:37:40.930
And the bad part about it
is I think any research that

00:37:40.930 --> 00:37:46.480
relies on surveys, revealed
behavior, or stated behavior

00:37:46.480 --> 00:37:49.120
is just no good anymore.

00:37:49.120 --> 00:37:50.820
It may have been
good in the past

00:37:50.820 --> 00:37:54.840
or they may have been lying
to us about how good it was.

00:37:54.840 --> 00:38:00.280
But right now, we need something
that looks at the real data.

00:38:00.280 --> 00:38:04.000
And so, this is where
the tracking data is key.

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:06.526
And it's starting to be done.

00:38:06.526 --> 00:38:11.680
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] I worked
in industry data before this.

00:38:11.680 --> 00:38:14.416
Most of the issues we
had in the private sector

00:38:14.416 --> 00:38:19.000
were overcome by making
the data fully anonymous.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:23.110
Is that still not the case
with these Transit systems?

00:38:23.110 --> 00:38:26.200
Couldn't you just have instead
of me being Scott Foster,

00:38:26.200 --> 00:38:28.740
I'd be number 12379.

00:38:28.740 --> 00:38:30.960
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:38:30.960 --> 00:38:34.360
It is clearly doable.

00:38:34.360 --> 00:38:35.540
And it is done.

00:38:35.540 --> 00:38:39.010
We hashed the names
and the serial numbers

00:38:39.010 --> 00:38:41.350
and all that stuff.

00:38:41.350 --> 00:38:46.030
But-- I just had a conversation
about this with a public agency

00:38:46.030 --> 00:38:48.730
person this morning--

00:38:48.730 --> 00:38:53.012
they get very concerned
about small numbers.

00:38:53.012 --> 00:38:54.970
And on Transit, there's
a lot of small numbers.

00:38:54.970 --> 00:38:59.080
If you're actually looking
at OD movements from A

00:38:59.080 --> 00:39:05.210
to B in the early morning,
there may be only a couple

00:39:05.210 --> 00:39:06.340
of people doing that.

00:39:06.340 --> 00:39:09.740
And so then they get
nervous about doing that.

00:39:09.740 --> 00:39:11.890
And I would argue that
those are the very things

00:39:11.890 --> 00:39:12.880
we want to learn about.

00:39:12.880 --> 00:39:16.280
Because you look at the bus.

00:39:16.280 --> 00:39:19.090
And you know it's full
at 8:00 in the morning.

00:39:19.090 --> 00:39:23.550
But where should that bus be,
maybe, at 6:00 in the morning?

00:39:23.550 --> 00:39:26.330
It maybe should be
somewhere very different.

00:39:26.330 --> 00:39:28.960
And we have to use this
automated data to do that.

00:39:28.960 --> 00:39:32.500
And we'd like to track
who who's using it

00:39:32.500 --> 00:39:33.610
and how they're using it.

00:39:33.610 --> 00:39:36.130
Because they might be using
it very, very differently.

00:39:36.130 --> 00:39:39.700
I don't know if you've noticed
this advocacy group, Transit

00:39:39.700 --> 00:39:45.190
Matters in the Boston area,
but they have this proposal

00:39:45.190 --> 00:39:46.600
for all night service.

00:39:46.600 --> 00:39:49.900
And it's different than
the late night service

00:39:49.900 --> 00:39:55.537
proposal in that it's looking
at service for workers early

00:39:55.537 --> 00:39:57.370
in the morning and at
the airport and things

00:39:57.370 --> 00:39:58.411
like-- this guy knows it.

00:39:58.411 --> 00:39:59.560
Yeah.

00:39:59.560 --> 00:40:00.110
He did.

00:40:00.110 --> 00:40:00.700
Yeah.

00:40:00.700 --> 00:40:01.199
OK.

00:40:05.500 --> 00:40:11.770
But anyway, it's just,
that makes sense.

00:40:11.770 --> 00:40:14.800
But what you don't
have is good data

00:40:14.800 --> 00:40:17.410
about who's using it where.

00:40:17.410 --> 00:40:22.690
And there's not enough out
there to really measure it,

00:40:22.690 --> 00:40:24.010
in that particular case.

00:40:24.010 --> 00:40:26.530
Because there would
be induced demand.

00:40:26.530 --> 00:40:31.275
AUDIENCE: So we can guess at
where people are going just

00:40:31.275 --> 00:40:36.260
by where [INAUDIBLE] can't get
the regularity when you get

00:40:36.260 --> 00:40:38.900
the small [INAUDIBLE]
And the private sector

00:40:38.900 --> 00:40:40.020
is the same thing.

00:40:40.020 --> 00:40:42.070
You have to make
sure you don't come

00:40:42.070 --> 00:40:44.500
close to identifying
an individual--

00:40:44.500 --> 00:40:45.695
customer level data.

00:40:45.695 --> 00:40:48.470
So it's always
aggregated in some way

00:40:48.470 --> 00:40:50.440
to make sure that you
couldn't figure it out.

00:40:50.440 --> 00:40:51.981
You have all the
people maybe getting

00:40:51.981 --> 00:40:56.329
on [INAUDIBLE] between
5:00 AM and 6:00 AM knowing

00:40:56.329 --> 00:40:57.370
that they got on at 5:05.

00:40:57.370 --> 00:40:58.036
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:40:58.036 --> 00:41:04.030
And there's a whole spectrum
here of what is acceptable

00:41:04.030 --> 00:41:05.720
and what is not.

00:41:05.720 --> 00:41:08.320
I guess, I just
argue, and I've said--

00:41:08.320 --> 00:41:13.030
I had a TRB talk
about five years ago

00:41:13.030 --> 00:41:20.960
about how the phone knows
when I'm near a pizza spot.

00:41:20.960 --> 00:41:23.860
And it sends me an ad.

00:41:23.860 --> 00:41:26.150
And I said, you know,
and if you actually

00:41:26.150 --> 00:41:30.740
look at the terms of use
of Google on those phones,

00:41:30.740 --> 00:41:33.620
it's like they can do
anything with that.

00:41:33.620 --> 00:41:36.500
They can look at
your phone call.

00:41:36.500 --> 00:41:38.390
If you actually
read those things,

00:41:38.390 --> 00:41:43.370
they use every piece of data
that they have accessible

00:41:43.370 --> 00:41:46.250
almost any way they want.

00:41:46.250 --> 00:41:49.130
And if you say you
decline, then you're

00:41:49.130 --> 00:41:52.270
location stuff
doesn't work ever.

00:41:52.270 --> 00:41:54.680
So it's a mess.

00:41:54.680 --> 00:41:57.890
And if these folks
can get you to do it,

00:41:57.890 --> 00:42:00.170
I say, well, the private
sector is doing it.

00:42:00.170 --> 00:42:05.600
There isn't many bad things
in the public sector.

00:42:05.600 --> 00:42:08.290
People think, oh, they'll
arrest you or something.

00:42:08.290 --> 00:42:11.745
And maybe, in this case,
maybe these days they will.

00:42:11.745 --> 00:42:12.286
I don't know.

00:42:12.286 --> 00:42:17.210
[LAUGHING] But in the old days,
when I was talking about this,

00:42:17.210 --> 00:42:18.590
I said, you know, come on.

00:42:18.590 --> 00:42:22.270
Let the government do its job in
the sense of planning services.

00:42:22.270 --> 00:42:23.130
Yeah.

00:42:23.130 --> 00:42:31.770
So one thing that
comes out of this,

00:42:31.770 --> 00:42:39.050
and this is customer information
and marketing combined,

00:42:39.050 --> 00:42:42.140
if we have a lot of this
automated fare data,

00:42:42.140 --> 00:42:45.440
on a voluntary basis, we
can create customer panels.

00:42:45.440 --> 00:42:50.450
So you can ask people, we'd
like to help plan things better.

00:42:50.450 --> 00:42:53.120
Let's put these panels together.

00:42:53.120 --> 00:42:56.704
We're going to use your
data for two months.

00:42:56.704 --> 00:42:59.120
And we want to ask you some
questions about your attitudes

00:42:59.120 --> 00:42:59.619
and things.

00:42:59.619 --> 00:43:04.640
And this is done a lot
in the private sector.

00:43:04.640 --> 00:43:07.100
When we've done it, a lot--

00:43:07.100 --> 00:43:11.210
anywhere between 35%
and 50% have said, yes.

00:43:11.210 --> 00:43:15.740
You can essentially do
this on an ongoing basis.

00:43:15.740 --> 00:43:18.020
And you can create
a very large panel.

00:43:18.020 --> 00:43:23.050
And you can randomly select
them for other little surveys.

00:43:23.050 --> 00:43:26.660
And then you could see if
they react with respect

00:43:26.660 --> 00:43:30.960
to their particular
travel behavior.

00:43:30.960 --> 00:43:34.580
And so, I think this
is the way we learn

00:43:34.580 --> 00:43:36.920
the travel behavior impacts.

00:43:36.920 --> 00:43:38.780
But you gotta get a big panel.

00:43:38.780 --> 00:43:41.690
And so far, the
transit agencies have

00:43:41.690 --> 00:43:43.430
been a little
worried about this,

00:43:43.430 --> 00:43:45.080
again, from the
privacy perspective.

00:43:45.080 --> 00:43:48.470
I say, if people agree,
there's no privacy issue.

00:43:51.120 --> 00:43:53.510
And then you can
continually enrich this.

00:43:53.510 --> 00:43:56.160
You could keep recruiting
people for this

00:43:56.160 --> 00:43:59.040
so that there is a lot of churn
in the transit ridership--

00:43:59.040 --> 00:44:03.720
that people don't stay
forever riding the bus.

00:44:03.720 --> 00:44:06.890
Because they move or they get
a new job or they buy a car.

00:44:12.890 --> 00:44:18.400
The thing you could then
move to is pilot programs.

00:44:18.400 --> 00:44:23.320
And you could select
people on these panels

00:44:23.320 --> 00:44:25.020
to be offered new things.

00:44:25.020 --> 00:44:26.800
And so this thing
that we're trying

00:44:26.800 --> 00:44:32.620
to get started with the CTA is
to do mobility as a service.

00:44:32.620 --> 00:44:34.600
So they have this Ventra app.

00:44:34.600 --> 00:44:37.690
It works really, really
well for transit.

00:44:37.690 --> 00:44:42.970
Well, why not put bike sharing,
car sharing, potentially TNCs

00:44:42.970 --> 00:44:44.590
on this app?

00:44:44.590 --> 00:44:48.310
And do it in a way
that the transit agency

00:44:48.310 --> 00:44:52.790
dictates who gets paid and
how much they get paid.

00:44:52.790 --> 00:44:55.120
And this is a big sell.

00:44:55.120 --> 00:44:58.570
Because they see Ubers and
Lyfts and the car-sharing people

00:44:58.570 --> 00:45:02.410
as the evil empire.

00:45:02.410 --> 00:45:07.630
But what we say is, do
it on a pilot basis,

00:45:07.630 --> 00:45:10.180
because you can get
these individual panels.

00:45:10.180 --> 00:45:14.260
You could do it on a
general public basis,

00:45:14.260 --> 00:45:15.730
if they volunteer.

00:45:15.730 --> 00:45:18.950
Or you could do it
through employers,

00:45:18.950 --> 00:45:22.480
which, then, is
another way transit,

00:45:22.480 --> 00:45:31.280
I think, has underutilized their
market strength, in a sense.

00:45:31.280 --> 00:45:37.190
Employers, in large
cities, have a motivation

00:45:37.190 --> 00:45:39.260
to promote transit.

00:45:39.260 --> 00:45:41.900
Because if they don't
promote transit,

00:45:41.900 --> 00:45:44.570
they have to make sure that
their employees can find

00:45:44.570 --> 00:45:46.421
parking near their offices.

00:45:46.421 --> 00:45:48.170
So they either have
to provide the parking

00:45:48.170 --> 00:45:51.140
or they have to provide
a parking subsidy.

00:45:51.140 --> 00:45:53.570
As many of you know, we
have been doing a lot here

00:45:53.570 --> 00:45:57.110
in MIT with this and trying
to change the behavior

00:45:57.110 --> 00:46:03.290
by essentially giving a free
transit pass to every employer

00:46:03.290 --> 00:46:08.210
and charging daily for
parking as opposed to what

00:46:08.210 --> 00:46:09.830
used to be a Either, Or.

00:46:09.830 --> 00:46:14.960
You pick transit or
you pick parking.

00:46:14.960 --> 00:46:18.630
You can do all these
things to learn.

00:46:18.630 --> 00:46:22.170
But what it all depends
on is this mobile data

00:46:22.170 --> 00:46:28.500
and other automated data
sources to tie it all together.

00:46:28.500 --> 00:46:31.700
I think one of the issues
that this will also help

00:46:31.700 --> 00:46:34.790
is you can get
feedback from people

00:46:34.790 --> 00:46:39.370
about what they want to know
when they want to know it.

00:46:39.370 --> 00:46:42.240
So you can't do that in a
fully-automated fashion.

00:46:42.240 --> 00:46:44.630
So these panels are
the only way that you

00:46:44.630 --> 00:46:49.430
can get to a large
representative group of people

00:46:49.430 --> 00:46:53.360
and quiz them about when
they had bad service

00:46:53.360 --> 00:46:57.360
and what they did and
what kind of information

00:46:57.360 --> 00:46:58.880
that you need to get to them.

00:47:01.830 --> 00:47:06.600
So the next four slides
are from Montreal.

00:47:06.600 --> 00:47:09.750
And Isabelle Trottier presented
them a couple of years

00:47:09.750 --> 00:47:12.630
ago when she came down here
to what we call the Transit

00:47:12.630 --> 00:47:14.430
Leaders Roundtable.

00:47:14.430 --> 00:47:18.420
And they are a little
bit ahead of the curve

00:47:18.420 --> 00:47:22.260
in terms of providing
mobility as a service.

00:47:22.260 --> 00:47:24.260
And I'll just give
you some examples.

00:47:24.260 --> 00:47:28.680
This is mostly
oriented towards biking

00:47:28.680 --> 00:47:31.680
in Montreal and bike sharing.

00:47:31.680 --> 00:47:35.070
But I picked it,
because I have an ax

00:47:35.070 --> 00:47:36.330
to grind about the biking.

00:47:36.330 --> 00:47:40.700
And so, I'm not
quite as bad as Fred.

00:47:40.700 --> 00:47:42.350
But I have a good example here.

00:47:42.350 --> 00:47:48.930
So the bicycles are
growing in popularity.

00:47:48.930 --> 00:47:52.020
I don't know exactly what
passport mobility is.

00:47:52.020 --> 00:47:54.100
I don't remember what it is.

00:47:54.100 --> 00:47:57.690
But it's essentially
a way to buy things.

00:47:57.690 --> 00:48:01.802
I think it's an account
that you can use.

00:48:01.802 --> 00:48:08.024
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:48:08.024 --> 00:48:08.690
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:48:11.860 --> 00:48:15.210
So the reason I picked
the bicycle here is this

00:48:15.210 --> 00:48:18.450
is a place that has been very
successful at combining bikes

00:48:18.450 --> 00:48:20.940
and buses in the same
lane, which we're

00:48:20.940 --> 00:48:24.360
having a huge fight here
in the Boston area about,

00:48:24.360 --> 00:48:27.280
whether it's safe or not.

00:48:27.280 --> 00:48:33.750
And they have done and recently
have been doing studies of this

00:48:33.750 --> 00:48:37.620
and looking at where it works
and where it doesn't work.

00:48:37.620 --> 00:48:41.550
And they've brought the bicycle
people in to see the data

00:48:41.550 --> 00:48:43.050
and do it transparently.

00:48:43.050 --> 00:48:45.150
And I argue, we have
to do this in Boston

00:48:45.150 --> 00:48:49.590
or else the MBTA is dead.

00:48:49.590 --> 00:48:51.450
There's a bunch of examples.

00:48:51.450 --> 00:48:53.850
The conclusion drawn from
the first pilot project

00:48:53.850 --> 00:48:57.520
was it's both possible
and even desirable.

00:48:57.520 --> 00:49:01.080
It's safe, and it's functional.

00:49:01.080 --> 00:49:03.570
The cyclists like it.

00:49:03.570 --> 00:49:06.990
The bus performance-- they used
to have the lane by themselves.

00:49:06.990 --> 00:49:08.070
Now they don't.

00:49:08.070 --> 00:49:10.890
It's not gone down.

00:49:10.890 --> 00:49:14.680
And they're deploying it
now, on a case by case basis,

00:49:14.680 --> 00:49:18.360
depending a little
bit on the layout

00:49:18.360 --> 00:49:21.300
of the streets and the lanes.

00:49:21.300 --> 00:49:26.940
And so my little commercial is
we need to do this for mobility

00:49:26.940 --> 00:49:29.610
in the Boston area.

00:49:29.610 --> 00:49:31.880
So my final slide
in this whole area

00:49:31.880 --> 00:49:37.850
is Lead to a Re-definition
of Public Transit.

00:49:37.850 --> 00:49:42.680
And I think that we're
almost there, at this point.

00:49:42.680 --> 00:49:46.220
All these mobility
services are being--

00:49:46.220 --> 00:49:48.980
the same people are using all
of these mobility services.

00:49:48.980 --> 00:49:52.050
There are now the
private car users.

00:49:52.050 --> 00:49:54.950
And there are people
using mobility services.

00:49:54.950 --> 00:49:59.600
And they're using a
combination of them.

00:49:59.600 --> 00:50:03.380
I did talk two
years ago when they

00:50:03.380 --> 00:50:09.440
did the first study of users in
the New York City area of Uber

00:50:09.440 --> 00:50:12.230
and taxis and public transit.

00:50:12.230 --> 00:50:15.620
And at the time, the
Uber fare in Manhattan

00:50:15.620 --> 00:50:22.740
averaged about $20, which
was still pretty high.

00:50:22.740 --> 00:50:28.520
And the analysis said that
if it got down to around $10,

00:50:28.520 --> 00:50:34.130
on average, and people used
1/3 third of their trips--

00:50:34.130 --> 00:50:35.870
all their trip making on Uber--

00:50:35.870 --> 00:50:40.520
and 2/3 on transit,
you would actually

00:50:40.520 --> 00:50:47.330
spend less on that combination
than buying a car even

00:50:47.330 --> 00:50:52.470
in the outer
Boroughs of New York.

00:50:52.470 --> 00:50:54.920
So what's happened
in the meantime

00:50:54.920 --> 00:50:57.170
is that Uber fares
have come down.

00:50:57.170 --> 00:51:00.620
And they're probably at that
level, as an average, now.

00:51:00.620 --> 00:51:04.520
So that means if you're
economically savvy,

00:51:04.520 --> 00:51:06.980
you're crazy to be
operating a car.

00:51:06.980 --> 00:51:09.701
Because, generally,
for the longer trips

00:51:09.701 --> 00:51:10.700
you can take the subway.

00:51:10.700 --> 00:51:14.180
And for the shorter
trips you take Uber.

00:51:14.180 --> 00:51:22.500
And the question is,
has it changed behavior?

00:51:22.500 --> 00:51:27.140
The New York City people say,
there's more cars in Manhattan.

00:51:27.140 --> 00:51:29.780
So that indicates there
are more people using Uber.

00:51:29.780 --> 00:51:32.180
Because they're not using more
private cars in Manhattan.

00:51:32.180 --> 00:51:36.030
Because they have
no place to park.

00:51:36.030 --> 00:51:41.240
So this is a thing
that transit is

00:51:41.240 --> 00:51:45.020
extremely worried about
but it's doing very little.

00:51:45.020 --> 00:51:52.880
And the question is, can
we control this in any way?

00:51:52.880 --> 00:51:54.860
And I would argue,
the only way they

00:51:54.860 --> 00:51:59.060
can do it is by having
a joint deal where

00:51:59.060 --> 00:52:04.910
they give information and
payment together on an app.

00:52:04.910 --> 00:52:08.354
And they give you
unlimited rides on transit.

00:52:08.354 --> 00:52:09.770
And they give you
a certain number

00:52:09.770 --> 00:52:12.380
of rides on these other modes.

00:52:12.380 --> 00:52:18.710
And basically, it's a good
economic deal for everyone.

00:52:18.710 --> 00:52:21.040
And you market it like that.

00:52:21.040 --> 00:52:26.180
Because frankly, transit
has been cutting back

00:52:26.180 --> 00:52:28.700
the really bad
off-peak services.

00:52:28.700 --> 00:52:34.250
Because they can't afford to
subsidize it at $10 a ride.

00:52:34.250 --> 00:52:38.210
And if they only subsidize--

00:52:38.210 --> 00:52:42.590
for example, you might give them
a certain number of Uber trips

00:52:42.590 --> 00:52:44.510
that are just to and
from rail stations.

00:52:44.510 --> 00:52:47.420
Because they can do
this geofencing thing.

00:52:47.420 --> 00:52:54.440
Or you might give a
subsidy for Uber trips

00:52:54.440 --> 00:52:59.260
up to a certain amount per trip
for a certain number of trips.

00:52:59.260 --> 00:53:02.330
There's a whole bunch of
bundling that you can do here.

00:53:02.330 --> 00:53:05.480
And what I'm saying
is that we gotta

00:53:05.480 --> 00:53:10.100
do this in a series of
controlled experiments

00:53:10.100 --> 00:53:14.520
and learn what people want
and what people use and learn,

00:53:14.520 --> 00:53:19.220
frankly, whether we're going
to end up being just high

00:53:19.220 --> 00:53:23.150
frequency corridor routes left.

00:53:23.150 --> 00:53:27.590
And there is a real
debate about this.

00:53:27.590 --> 00:53:31.580
And there's a real
debate about whether this

00:53:31.580 --> 00:53:37.014
is where we're going to end up
or whether Uber and Lyft are

00:53:37.014 --> 00:53:38.180
going to go out of business.

00:53:38.180 --> 00:53:41.960
Because they, right now,
have unsustainable fares.

00:53:41.960 --> 00:53:46.040
That's what the transit
people hope and bet on.

00:53:46.040 --> 00:53:48.840
But I'm not sure that's
going to happen or not.

00:53:48.840 --> 00:53:50.460
So, yeah.

00:53:50.460 --> 00:53:52.572
AUDIENCE: That's what's
really interesting to me.

00:53:52.572 --> 00:53:55.084
I definitely agree these
are going to have phenomenal

00:53:55.084 --> 00:53:55.584
impact..

00:53:55.584 --> 00:53:58.790
But in London, they are
investing huge amounts

00:53:58.790 --> 00:54:01.832
of money for Crossrail
and Crossrail 2, which

00:54:01.832 --> 00:54:04.260
are high frequency routes.

00:54:04.260 --> 00:54:07.530
But in cities where
the road layout is not

00:54:07.530 --> 00:54:14.470
a grid they have to
scale larger, [INAUDIBLE]

00:54:14.470 --> 00:54:15.650
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:54:15.650 --> 00:54:20.060
And London's doing it largely
on the economic theory

00:54:20.060 --> 00:54:21.530
of agglomeration--

00:54:21.530 --> 00:54:26.210
that they have such a density
of employment opportunities

00:54:26.210 --> 00:54:30.120
and other activities
that are altogether,

00:54:30.120 --> 00:54:33.620
they should have an economic
benefit to the thing.

00:54:33.620 --> 00:54:36.500
Frankly, every
developed country,

00:54:36.500 --> 00:54:39.710
every almost developing
country in the world

00:54:39.710 --> 00:54:45.350
is doing more investment in
transit than the United States.

00:54:45.350 --> 00:54:49.700
And Fred would argue
that we should just

00:54:49.700 --> 00:54:52.730
forget about all this stuff
and just build more rail

00:54:52.730 --> 00:54:56.260
lines in certain places.

00:54:56.260 --> 00:54:58.970
I think that, in
many cities, we're

00:54:58.970 --> 00:55:00.860
beyond a little bit of that.

00:55:00.860 --> 00:55:04.400
Because the sprawl is so great.

00:55:04.400 --> 00:55:04.910
It's right.

00:55:04.910 --> 00:55:08.570
In the big old cities,
the densities--

00:55:08.570 --> 00:55:12.240
if we want to increase the
density in Boston or in New

00:55:12.240 --> 00:55:16.620
York or Philadelphia, yes,
you have to have rail.

00:55:16.620 --> 00:55:19.750
Because essentially, you can't
increase the density anymore.

00:55:19.750 --> 00:55:21.570
Because there's no
place to put the cars.

00:55:21.570 --> 00:55:24.630
But in some of these other
cities that are spread out

00:55:24.630 --> 00:55:29.250
more, it's just not as
clear of what you should

00:55:29.250 --> 00:55:31.890
do in terms of investment.

00:55:31.890 --> 00:55:32.403
Yeah.

00:55:32.403 --> 00:55:33.236
AUDIENCE: I'm sorry.

00:55:33.236 --> 00:55:35.210
You said that
transit authorities

00:55:35.210 --> 00:55:37.670
are worried about this.

00:55:37.670 --> 00:55:41.560
[INAUDIBLE]

00:55:41.560 --> 00:55:46.630
PROFESSOR: Nationally,
for the last decade,

00:55:46.630 --> 00:55:50.370
transit ridership
has gone up steadily.

00:55:50.370 --> 00:55:52.510
And everybody was really happy.

00:55:52.510 --> 00:55:55.750
The last two to three
years, bus ridership-- not

00:55:55.750 --> 00:55:58.510
rail ridership-- bus
ridership has gone down.

00:55:58.510 --> 00:56:00.280
And all the large cities.

00:56:00.280 --> 00:56:03.180
And everybody's debating about
what's the cause of that.

00:56:03.180 --> 00:56:05.350
Is it just the gas prices?

00:56:05.350 --> 00:56:07.750
Is it Uber and Lyft?

00:56:07.750 --> 00:56:09.430
What is it?

00:56:09.430 --> 00:56:11.570
And they're worried.

00:56:11.570 --> 00:56:12.070
Yeah.

00:56:12.070 --> 00:56:18.714
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:56:18.714 --> 00:56:19.630
PROFESSOR: Nationally?

00:56:19.630 --> 00:56:20.129
Yeah.

00:56:23.380 --> 00:56:27.254
There's a big debate about
why did D.C. has gone down.

00:56:27.254 --> 00:56:28.920
Because they've had
all these disruption

00:56:28.920 --> 00:56:31.440
because of the
safety and because

00:56:31.440 --> 00:56:34.410
of the reconstruction of things.

00:56:34.410 --> 00:56:36.210
So D.C. is a special case.

00:56:36.210 --> 00:56:38.740
But New York flattened out.

00:56:38.740 --> 00:56:39.510
That's right.

00:56:39.510 --> 00:56:41.590
And New York was going up.

00:56:41.590 --> 00:56:47.250
And nobody can argue it's the
economy, because the economy

00:56:47.250 --> 00:56:48.690
has been growing.

00:56:52.094 --> 00:56:52.594
Yeah.

00:56:52.594 --> 00:57:00.070
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:57:00.070 --> 00:57:00.976
PROFESSOR: Go ahead.

00:57:00.976 --> 00:57:03.252
[LAUGHING] He knows
this better than I do.

00:57:03.252 --> 00:57:06.912
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:57:06.912 --> 00:57:08.620
PROFESSOR: They're
skeptical in Montreal?

00:57:08.620 --> 00:57:09.115
AUDIENCE: Can't decide it.

00:57:09.115 --> 00:57:10.706
There is skepticism in Montreal.

00:57:13.570 --> 00:57:16.240
In theory it should work.

00:57:16.240 --> 00:57:19.346
Because buses and some high
schools average the same speed.

00:57:24.670 --> 00:57:27.920
In practice, the cyclist
goes 15 miles an hour.

00:57:27.920 --> 00:57:30.150
The bus goes
zero/thirty zero/thirty

00:57:30.150 --> 00:57:33.320
So there might be a
leapfrog leaping out anyway.

00:57:33.320 --> 00:57:38.310
I think what the
issue is that cyclists

00:57:38.310 --> 00:57:40.710
feel that they might get
squeezed [? there. ?]

00:57:40.710 --> 00:57:41.560
There's two issues.

00:57:41.560 --> 00:57:43.210
One is that if you just have--

00:57:43.210 --> 00:57:46.140
I think for really short
segments, these makes sense.

00:57:46.140 --> 00:57:52.080
For [INAUDIBLE] you're probably
thinking of [INAUDIBLE]..

00:57:52.080 --> 00:57:54.090
A couple hundred yards
with a huge bottleneck.

00:57:54.090 --> 00:57:57.360
And frankly, if a bus
had to follow a cyclist

00:57:57.360 --> 00:57:59.340
at 8 miles an hour, [INAUDIBLE]

00:57:59.340 --> 00:57:59.890
PROFESSOR: It wouldn't matter.

00:57:59.890 --> 00:58:02.223
AUDIENCE: It would still be
much faster than a car going

00:58:02.223 --> 00:58:03.480
two or three lights.

00:58:03.480 --> 00:58:09.110
But in longer corridors,
especially where

00:58:09.110 --> 00:58:12.120
you have the bus pulling
from the curve and back,

00:58:12.120 --> 00:58:14.330
it becomes more of an issue.

00:58:14.330 --> 00:58:16.350
There's the question of
whether you could build

00:58:16.350 --> 00:58:17.680
some kind of floating bus stop.

00:58:17.680 --> 00:58:19.430
So you'd have separation
at the bus stops.

00:58:19.430 --> 00:58:22.120
And the vehicles would
never have to cross paths.

00:58:22.120 --> 00:58:23.930
And the buses could
pass the cyclists.

00:58:23.930 --> 00:58:26.690
And the cyclists could pass
the buses where needed.

00:58:26.690 --> 00:58:31.337
But that's more, I think, cities
sort of see this as a panacea

00:58:31.337 --> 00:58:33.420
where they can lay down
some [INAUDIBLE] for that.

00:58:33.420 --> 00:58:35.037
And it's not a
problem [INAUDIBLE]

00:58:35.037 --> 00:58:36.620
mention that in
[INAUDIBLE] in Madison

00:58:36.620 --> 00:58:38.830
they have shared bus bike lanes.

00:58:38.830 --> 00:58:40.510
And they work pretty well.

00:58:43.100 --> 00:58:44.620
And I don't disagree.

00:58:44.620 --> 00:58:46.690
But those are also some
five lane wide streets

00:58:46.690 --> 00:58:51.224
where they can provide
a really wide facility.

00:58:51.224 --> 00:58:51.890
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:58:51.890 --> 00:58:54.920
It does depend on the
width of the lane.

00:58:54.920 --> 00:58:59.270
I agree [INAUDIBLE] agree that
we could do a lot with queue

00:58:59.270 --> 00:59:00.110
jump lanes--

00:59:00.110 --> 00:59:03.290
not fully dedicated lanes.

00:59:03.290 --> 00:59:08.240
We can't give up a full lane all
the way up and down Mass Ave.

00:59:08.240 --> 00:59:10.730
But in front of MIT, we can.

00:59:10.730 --> 00:59:14.480
From the river to
Albany Street, we can.

00:59:14.480 --> 00:59:18.290
Because there's no
commercial activity.

00:59:18.290 --> 00:59:23.825
We have 17 parking spaces out
here in front of 77 Mass Ave.

00:59:23.825 --> 00:59:24.710
17 spaces.

00:59:24.710 --> 00:59:27.740
You can put them on
Amherst Alley really easily

00:59:27.740 --> 00:59:29.510
and have all this
space that we could

00:59:29.510 --> 00:59:31.340
devote for bikes and buses.

00:59:31.340 --> 00:59:35.780
So what I would argue is,
we need queue jump lanes.

00:59:35.780 --> 00:59:37.910
A lot of people talk about--

00:59:37.910 --> 00:59:41.100
did Peter Firth
talk about TSP yet?

00:59:41.100 --> 00:59:41.600
OK.

00:59:41.600 --> 00:59:42.170
He's coming.

00:59:42.170 --> 00:59:45.860
Peter's going to come and talk
about Transit Signal Priority.

00:59:45.860 --> 00:59:48.290
And listen carefully.

00:59:48.290 --> 00:59:52.760
Because transit signal priority
provides very, very small

00:59:52.760 --> 00:59:58.310
improvements, especially if
the bus is stuck behind a car.

00:59:58.310 --> 01:00:04.970
And so, the question is,
transit signal priority

01:00:04.970 --> 01:00:09.260
works well when at the
congested intersections

01:00:09.260 --> 01:00:12.530
we have a queue jump lane
that the bus can get around

01:00:12.530 --> 01:00:17.030
the long line of cars that
might be there in the rush hour.

01:00:17.030 --> 01:00:19.360
And so we need both.

01:00:19.360 --> 01:00:23.180
And what I would argue is
that in those small segments,

01:00:23.180 --> 01:00:26.628
the buses can share
it with bikes.

01:00:26.628 --> 01:00:30.090
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:00:30.090 --> 01:00:32.600
PROFESSOR: Enforcement.

01:00:32.600 --> 01:00:33.210
Yeah.

