But around here,
as Ari says, you

01:01:09.010 --> 01:01:13.150
know if we get seven or eight
miles an hour out of a bus,

01:01:13.150 --> 01:01:14.560
we're happy.

01:01:14.560 --> 01:01:16.740
Because they're only
average four or five.

01:01:16.740 --> 01:01:17.240
[LAUGHING]

01:01:17.240 --> 01:01:19.700
AUDIENCE: That seven
or eight miles an hour

01:01:19.700 --> 01:01:22.226
is enough to get to a
light that's actually

01:01:22.226 --> 01:01:25.802
held green for ten seconds so if
that light changes [INAUDIBLE]..

01:01:30.430 --> 01:01:32.394
AUDIENCE: I don't see
why that problem is

01:01:32.394 --> 01:01:33.955
unique to the facility.

01:01:33.955 --> 01:01:39.210
Because even if the bus is
sharing a lane of traffic

01:01:39.210 --> 01:01:40.984
and the bike lane
is not a bike lane,

01:01:40.984 --> 01:01:42.442
there's still
[INAUDIBLE] conflict.

01:01:44.540 --> 01:01:46.010
AUDIENCE: That's certainly true.

01:01:46.010 --> 01:01:49.020
I think what the issue
is that cyclists--

01:01:49.020 --> 01:01:50.910
some cyclists can
be very special.

01:01:50.910 --> 01:01:53.529
And I'm not talking about
anyone who works at the City

01:01:53.529 --> 01:01:54.112
of Cambridge..

01:01:57.030 --> 01:02:01.140
There are some cycling
advocates who would rather--

01:02:01.140 --> 01:02:03.020
there are some cyclists
and cycling advocates

01:02:03.020 --> 01:02:06.130
who don't understand that
there were transit issues

01:02:06.130 --> 01:02:08.320
before traffic [INAUDIBLE].

01:02:08.320 --> 01:02:13.970
And there needs to be a bit of
a detente between the cyclists

01:02:13.970 --> 01:02:15.204
and the transit users.

01:02:15.204 --> 01:02:17.120
The problem-- I think
Frank pointed this out--

01:02:17.120 --> 01:02:19.244
is that the cyclists are
meant for [INAUDIBLE] more

01:02:19.244 --> 01:02:22.990
organizers than cyclists who are
put in mortal danger every time

01:02:22.990 --> 01:02:23.990
they're going somewhere.

01:02:23.990 --> 01:02:27.400
And transit users are
just like [INAUDIBLE]..

01:02:27.400 --> 01:02:31.100
And there's a difference
between those two groups.

01:02:31.100 --> 01:02:35.930
And I know that this
past November, I

01:02:35.930 --> 01:02:40.130
think in the past fall I'm on
the Cambridge Cycling Committee

01:02:40.130 --> 01:02:42.650
and I try to be
a voice of reason

01:02:42.650 --> 01:02:45.100
for transit as well on
those bicycle committees.

01:02:45.100 --> 01:02:45.650
[INAUDIBLE]

01:02:45.650 --> 01:02:47.150
PROFESSOR: The only
voice of reason.

01:02:47.150 --> 01:02:47.650
No.

01:02:47.650 --> 01:02:48.670
[LAUGHING]

01:02:48.670 --> 01:02:51.610
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
sometimes there

01:02:51.610 --> 01:02:58.310
can be [INAUDIBLE]
bus stops on Mass Ave.

01:02:58.310 --> 01:03:01.430
PROFESSOR: Because 40% of the
people on Mass Ave in the rush

01:03:01.430 --> 01:03:02.180
hour are on buses.

01:03:04.510 --> 01:03:05.010
Yeah.

01:03:05.010 --> 01:03:08.327
AUDIENCE: And 50% of
them are on bikes.

01:03:08.327 --> 01:03:09.410
PROFESSOR: It's even more.

01:03:09.410 --> 01:03:09.910
Yeah.

01:03:09.910 --> 01:03:11.210
It's almost 50%.

01:03:11.210 --> 01:03:12.680
Yeah.

01:03:12.680 --> 01:03:14.844
And a lot of the
arterials around here,

01:03:14.844 --> 01:03:15.760
that's the percentage.

01:03:15.760 --> 01:03:19.310
It's between 35% and 50%
of the people are on buses.

01:03:19.310 --> 01:03:21.893
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] The bike
doesn't take up that much room.

01:03:26.910 --> 01:03:32.297
So the issue, I think,
winds up being that--

01:03:32.297 --> 01:03:33.630
PROFESSOR: We're off topic here.

01:03:33.630 --> 01:03:34.510
[LAUGHING]

01:03:34.510 --> 01:03:36.052
AUDIENCE: We had a
nice conversation.

01:03:36.052 --> 01:03:38.093
I think when you get people
in the same room they

01:03:38.093 --> 01:03:40.320
start to understand that
there's a give and take.

01:03:40.320 --> 01:03:41.300
[INAUDIBLE] and
I said, if you're

01:03:41.300 --> 01:03:42.990
doing planning an
isolation where you talk

01:03:42.990 --> 01:03:45.130
to bike people and they, say, we
want X and you talk to transit

01:03:45.130 --> 01:03:47.640
people and they say they
want Y, the easiest thing

01:03:47.640 --> 01:03:48.348
is to do nothing.

01:03:48.348 --> 01:03:51.300
[INAUDIBLE]

01:03:51.300 --> 01:03:53.040
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:03:53.040 --> 01:03:57.210
I think the bus
lane actually gets--

01:03:57.210 --> 01:03:59.880
although, these
days I'm not sure--

01:03:59.880 --> 01:04:05.130
but I would say that the bus
lanes get more adverse reaction

01:04:05.130 --> 01:04:07.560
from the drivers than
the bike lanes do.

01:04:07.560 --> 01:04:11.490
Because they don't seem to
take away driving lanes.

01:04:11.490 --> 01:04:14.010
Whereas a bus lane
seems to either take

01:04:14.010 --> 01:04:16.770
a driving or a
parking lane away.

01:04:16.770 --> 01:04:21.300
And so, it gets more
opposition from the drivers.

01:04:21.300 --> 01:04:24.990
But there's a quote.

01:04:24.990 --> 01:04:27.580
I forget the quote now.

01:04:27.580 --> 01:04:32.110
But basically,
urbanologists-- people--

01:04:32.110 --> 01:04:34.440
have started to
realize that we're

01:04:34.440 --> 01:04:37.920
spending tons and tons of
money doing bike facilities

01:04:37.920 --> 01:04:39.360
in these urban areas.

01:04:39.360 --> 01:04:42.570
And we're spending nothing
on transit facilities.

01:04:42.570 --> 01:04:46.320
And that's a long-term disaster.

01:04:46.320 --> 01:04:50.760
Because essentially,
there is a limit

01:04:50.760 --> 01:04:54.780
on the amount of bike use, I
think, in any of these places.

01:04:54.780 --> 01:04:56.700
Because there's lots of people.

01:04:56.700 --> 01:04:57.780
I used to bike.

01:04:57.780 --> 01:04:59.580
I live four miles away.

01:04:59.580 --> 01:05:00.240
I used to bike.

01:05:00.240 --> 01:05:01.350
I'm getting old.

01:05:01.350 --> 01:05:06.851
So I'm losing a little bit of my
perception and stuff like that.

01:05:06.851 --> 01:05:08.100
I had a couple of close calls.

01:05:08.100 --> 01:05:09.330
I stopped.

01:05:09.330 --> 01:05:10.920
I basically just stopped.

01:05:10.920 --> 01:05:12.600
I said, I'll bike
when I go to Cape Cod.

01:05:12.600 --> 01:05:14.490
I'm not going to bike
in these streets.

01:05:14.490 --> 01:05:16.410
Mainly I was afraid
of the other bikers

01:05:16.410 --> 01:05:21.670
then I was as opposed to
being afraid of the cars.

01:05:21.670 --> 01:05:25.700
And there's lots of
people that just can't.

01:05:25.700 --> 01:05:27.630
And a lot of those people
want to take buses.

01:05:27.630 --> 01:05:31.590
But they also don't want to be
held up in congestion streets

01:05:31.590 --> 01:05:32.860
all the time.

01:05:32.860 --> 01:05:35.530
So can we switch?

01:05:35.530 --> 01:05:37.120
I don't know your computer.

01:05:37.120 --> 01:05:38.700
Can we switch to the other one?

01:05:38.700 --> 01:05:41.640
We'll just get started on
the Performance Measurement.

01:05:41.640 --> 01:05:45.750
And then we'll go
into the next one.

01:05:51.195 --> 01:05:52.690
Great.

01:05:52.690 --> 01:05:55.770
The reading, I
think, is important.

01:05:58.890 --> 01:06:01.290
It's a dry topic.

01:06:01.290 --> 01:06:05.340
It's how transit authorities
evaluate themselves

01:06:05.340 --> 01:06:08.400
and how they evaluate themselves
with respect to other transit

01:06:08.400 --> 01:06:10.510
authorities.

01:06:10.510 --> 01:06:11.670
But it's important.

01:06:11.670 --> 01:06:17.820
Because if they don't do
performance measurement,

01:06:17.820 --> 01:06:19.050
nobody improves.

01:06:19.050 --> 01:06:20.970
And there's example
after example.

01:06:20.970 --> 01:06:24.810
The two best examples,
from my perspective,

01:06:24.810 --> 01:06:27.240
are the CTA, about
five years ago,

01:06:27.240 --> 01:06:31.950
instituted this rigorous
performance measurements regime

01:06:31.950 --> 01:06:39.000
that the general manager
sat at a weekly meeting

01:06:39.000 --> 01:06:41.160
on a rotating basis
with every department

01:06:41.160 --> 01:06:42.810
and developed
performance measures

01:06:42.810 --> 01:06:45.180
and tracked them
for each department.

01:06:45.180 --> 01:06:49.810
And the performance, almost
universally, went up.

01:06:49.810 --> 01:06:52.470
There's a set of slides
that I can't go over.

01:06:52.470 --> 01:06:56.850
But we'll put on
Stellar about this.

01:06:56.850 --> 01:07:01.660
It's an amazing story, I think.

01:07:01.660 --> 01:07:03.600
The GM was only
there for two years.

01:07:03.600 --> 01:07:07.770
He was one of these
management by data types.

01:07:07.770 --> 01:07:10.680
And then he got moved to
run the school department,

01:07:10.680 --> 01:07:11.400
for God's sake.

01:07:11.400 --> 01:07:13.470
I don't know why.

01:07:13.470 --> 01:07:15.120
But, anyway.

01:07:15.120 --> 01:07:18.630
And the other example
really is the MBTA

01:07:18.630 --> 01:07:22.740
under the fiscal management
control board, where they've

01:07:22.740 --> 01:07:25.980
insisted that there
be regular updates

01:07:25.980 --> 01:07:29.820
and data-driven analyses.

01:07:29.820 --> 01:07:35.220
And if you look at the progress
on things like Overtime,

01:07:35.220 --> 01:07:42.000
and essentially, things that
are inefficient, generally,

01:07:42.000 --> 01:07:43.410
they've improved.

01:07:43.410 --> 01:07:46.710
And there's a lot more to
improve here at the MBTA.

01:07:46.710 --> 01:07:49.170
And there's a lot
of issues that can't

01:07:49.170 --> 01:07:53.310
be solved just by better
management and performance

01:07:53.310 --> 01:07:54.560
measurement.

01:07:54.560 --> 01:07:56.100
But there's a lot that can.

01:07:56.100 --> 01:08:02.560
And so, I think this is
a really important topic.

01:08:02.560 --> 01:08:07.320
So what we have
here is a little bit

01:08:07.320 --> 01:08:09.720
of justification of doing this.

01:08:09.720 --> 01:08:12.480
There is an older report
that's really good--

01:08:12.480 --> 01:08:17.430
TCRP 88 that essentially
is a cookbook

01:08:17.430 --> 01:08:19.200
on how to develop a
performance management

01:08:19.200 --> 01:08:21.270
system for your transit agency.

01:08:21.270 --> 01:08:25.290
And it's a really good report
with respect to the measures

01:08:25.290 --> 01:08:26.220
you use.

01:08:26.220 --> 01:08:29.970
And they divide into small,
medium, and large urban areas.

01:08:29.970 --> 01:08:34.380
And they give different measures
for four different ones.

01:08:34.380 --> 01:08:36.910
A lot of people want to compare
themselves to other people.

01:08:36.910 --> 01:08:38.640
There's this national database.

01:08:38.640 --> 01:08:42.689
And this is the website.

01:08:42.689 --> 01:08:45.060
And you can see
performance measures

01:08:45.060 --> 01:08:49.290
from everyone in the
country on a pretty much

01:08:49.290 --> 01:08:52.779
equitable reasonable basis.

01:08:52.779 --> 01:08:56.130
And then there's the concept
of performance audits, which

01:08:56.130 --> 01:08:58.260
we'll talk a little bit about.

01:08:58.260 --> 01:09:02.490
So why do it?

01:09:02.490 --> 01:09:04.410
Basically, whatever
gets measured

01:09:04.410 --> 01:09:07.700
gets noticed by management.

01:09:07.700 --> 01:09:11.340
And everybody's into these
new management dashboards

01:09:11.340 --> 01:09:13.900
with key performance indicators.

01:09:16.620 --> 01:09:20.200
It can be done and
not have an impact.

01:09:20.200 --> 01:09:24.180
But I feel like,
whatever that indicator

01:09:24.180 --> 01:09:26.609
is, people manage to it.

01:09:26.609 --> 01:09:29.160
Sometimes the indicator
is the wrong indicator.

01:09:29.160 --> 01:09:31.319
And it's not so good.

01:09:31.319 --> 01:09:36.840
Because it's the easy one to
measure as opposed to what

01:09:36.840 --> 01:09:39.029
they should be focused on.

01:09:39.029 --> 01:09:41.399
Many of them are--

01:09:41.399 --> 01:09:45.630
the measures that the board
and the top management look at

01:09:45.630 --> 01:09:48.750
are oriented to the
supply of the transit--

01:09:48.750 --> 01:09:51.300
what the vehicles did
as opposed to what

01:09:51.300 --> 01:09:55.380
the passenger experienced.

01:09:55.380 --> 01:09:59.550
The best example
of that is when you

01:09:59.550 --> 01:10:03.750
look at on-time performance.

01:10:03.750 --> 01:10:05.370
They measure it
within 2 or 3 minutes.

01:10:07.880 --> 01:10:12.030
And that doesn't mean anything
if the bus is supposed

01:10:12.030 --> 01:10:14.310
to come every 7 or 8 minutes.

01:10:14.310 --> 01:10:21.990
Because basically, there's
this phenomenon of long gaps

01:10:21.990 --> 01:10:24.330
and then followed by bunches.

01:10:24.330 --> 01:10:27.660
There's very few passengers
on the bunch buses, especially

01:10:27.660 --> 01:10:30.830
the second and third one.

01:10:30.830 --> 01:10:34.260
And most of the people
are on the crowded bus

01:10:34.260 --> 01:10:37.080
who had to wait, which
is the first one.

01:10:37.080 --> 01:10:39.600
And they had to wait
much longer for that.

01:10:39.600 --> 01:10:45.360
So the wait time for
passengers is not

01:10:45.360 --> 01:10:49.410
linearly related to this
on-time performance measure

01:10:49.410 --> 01:10:50.590
that they have.

01:10:50.590 --> 01:10:54.270
So you actually should be
trying to measure effective wait

01:10:54.270 --> 01:10:58.210
time for all passengers.

01:10:58.210 --> 01:11:00.510
And that should be
your measure for most

01:11:00.510 --> 01:11:03.380
of the transit services.

01:11:03.380 --> 01:11:07.100
They also use some of
the performance measures

01:11:07.100 --> 01:11:09.450
on a system basis for
funding allocation.

01:11:09.450 --> 01:11:11.870
I'll mention a few things there.

01:11:11.870 --> 01:11:14.525
I talked about this TCRP Report.

01:11:18.260 --> 01:11:20.180
It's nice.

01:11:20.180 --> 01:11:24.276
And I think it used to have
a website associated with it.

01:11:24.276 --> 01:11:25.650
So you could
actually go in there

01:11:25.650 --> 01:11:27.290
and put your own
program together.

01:11:27.290 --> 01:11:28.790
I'm not sure if it still does.

01:11:28.790 --> 01:11:30.110
Because it's fairly old.

01:11:30.110 --> 01:11:36.470
But it's nice in that it
isn't one prescribed thing.

01:11:36.470 --> 01:11:38.450
It gives you a lot
of different options.

01:11:38.450 --> 01:11:41.300
And you can tailor it
to your urban area.

01:11:45.120 --> 01:11:50.490
This is the process that
they recommend in the report.

01:11:50.490 --> 01:11:53.460
Again, this is an internal
performance measurement

01:11:53.460 --> 01:11:53.970
system--

01:11:53.970 --> 01:11:56.190
performance management system.

01:11:56.190 --> 01:12:02.190
And it's a top-down to find
your goals and objectives get

01:12:02.190 --> 01:12:03.300
management support.

01:12:03.300 --> 01:12:08.590
And I guess, the second
one is extremely important.

01:12:08.590 --> 01:12:12.600
I used to, as my olden
days as a consultant,

01:12:12.600 --> 01:12:16.800
I used to do transit performance
audits for transit agencies.

01:12:16.800 --> 01:12:21.570
And the experiences
varied further

01:12:21.570 --> 01:12:24.300
than anyone could imagine.

01:12:24.300 --> 01:12:26.490
I'd been in some
transit authorities.

01:12:26.490 --> 01:12:28.870
The first meeting was
with the general manager.

01:12:28.870 --> 01:12:33.170
And he says, go get 'em.

01:12:33.170 --> 01:12:35.490
And he says, and come back
with all the information,

01:12:35.490 --> 01:12:37.400
because I want to know it.

01:12:37.400 --> 01:12:39.920
And you would do it.

01:12:39.920 --> 01:12:42.590
And we'd come back
with the indicators.

01:12:42.590 --> 01:12:45.480
And he'd say, OK, what
do I do about this?

01:12:45.480 --> 01:12:46.810
What I do about this?

01:12:46.810 --> 01:12:48.590
He'd bring the
departments in and says,

01:12:48.590 --> 01:12:50.600
I'm not blaming anybody.

01:12:50.600 --> 01:12:52.370
We just gotta
develop action plans

01:12:52.370 --> 01:12:54.140
to get these things better.

01:12:54.140 --> 01:12:56.150
And I've been in
other properties

01:12:56.150 --> 01:12:59.270
where the general
manager said, literally,

01:12:59.270 --> 01:13:02.420
on the first
meeting, you're here

01:13:02.420 --> 01:13:06.090
because the state
makes me do this.

01:13:06.090 --> 01:13:11.090
So I want you to get in and out
of here as quick as you can.

01:13:11.090 --> 01:13:15.470
And basically, I know
how to manage my place.

01:13:15.470 --> 01:13:17.260
You don't have to
tell me anything.

01:13:17.260 --> 01:13:23.350
And now, all of these were
relatively small properties.

01:13:23.350 --> 01:13:25.520
We did some larger properties.

01:13:25.520 --> 01:13:30.430
But basically, there's
a tremendous variation

01:13:30.430 --> 01:13:32.920
among management styles on this.

01:13:32.920 --> 01:13:36.940
And so, if you're
going to do this,

01:13:36.940 --> 01:13:40.060
you want top management to be
supportive right from the start

01:13:40.060 --> 01:13:42.940
and to participate
in developing it.

01:13:45.772 --> 01:13:49.250
The rest of it is intuitive.

01:13:49.250 --> 01:13:52.160
The most important
thing is, how do

01:13:52.160 --> 01:13:54.920
the results, when you
update all these measures,

01:13:54.920 --> 01:13:58.190
get integrated into
how you actually

01:13:58.190 --> 01:13:59.990
carry out the business?

01:13:59.990 --> 01:14:03.300
And that is a hard
part sometimes.

01:14:03.300 --> 01:14:07.190
And it's a part that
you need to think about.

01:14:07.190 --> 01:14:11.210
And you gotta think about, what
can I do about this indicator?

01:14:11.210 --> 01:14:13.970
And I think part of
when you're deciding

01:14:13.970 --> 01:14:17.870
what the indicators are,
that's a big part is thinking

01:14:17.870 --> 01:14:21.190
about that step 7 and 8.

01:14:21.190 --> 01:14:24.050
And essentially, if
something's working

01:14:24.050 --> 01:14:25.880
and you're making
progress, you keep it in.

01:14:25.880 --> 01:14:31.130
If you don't, an 8, you throw
it out and try something else.

01:14:31.130 --> 01:14:37.850
This is the way they've got
lists and lists of measures.

01:14:37.850 --> 01:14:39.790
They've got bunches of tables.

01:14:39.790 --> 01:14:43.910
And again, they have them
for large properties.

01:14:43.910 --> 01:14:46.790
It makes sense for large
properties, medium, small,

01:14:46.790 --> 01:14:49.850
actually under 50,000 people
in the metropolitan area.

01:14:49.850 --> 01:14:52.580
So they basically
say, this is kind

01:14:52.580 --> 01:14:54.800
of what we think
your capabilities are

01:14:54.800 --> 01:15:00.180
based on staffing and
these kind of properties.

01:15:00.180 --> 01:15:01.210
There's some more.

01:15:01.210 --> 01:15:02.750
I'm not going to
go through these.

01:15:02.750 --> 01:15:06.190
The NDT data.

01:15:06.190 --> 01:15:08.320
How many people have
actually gone in

01:15:08.320 --> 01:15:09.830
and looked at these tables?

01:15:09.830 --> 01:15:11.230
Anybody?

01:15:11.230 --> 01:15:12.330
Two.

01:15:12.330 --> 01:15:13.470
OK.

01:15:13.470 --> 01:15:14.820
You should all do this.

01:15:14.820 --> 01:15:18.180
It's pretty interesting.

01:15:18.180 --> 01:15:20.910
They've got a whole range
of transit properties

01:15:20.910 --> 01:15:22.660
across the country.

01:15:22.660 --> 01:15:25.530
And you can sort
them in various ways.

01:15:25.530 --> 01:15:26.850
You can download reports.

01:15:26.850 --> 01:15:29.760
You can download
it in CSV files.

01:15:29.760 --> 01:15:33.890
You can see how your city
stacks up against other cities.

01:15:33.890 --> 01:15:36.460
Consultants use
these all the time.

01:15:36.460 --> 01:15:38.760
And the good thing about
it is at the beginning when

01:15:38.760 --> 01:15:41.880
they first developed
this, definitions

01:15:41.880 --> 01:15:44.760
were variable across cities.

01:15:44.760 --> 01:15:49.200
And each year, the
government has done

01:15:49.200 --> 01:15:51.420
what big bureaucracies do well.

01:15:51.420 --> 01:15:55.020
They started to
standardize this.

01:15:55.020 --> 01:15:57.910
And they call you up if
they don't like your number.

01:15:57.910 --> 01:16:00.300
And they also call you
up if your numbers change

01:16:00.300 --> 01:16:02.400
from year to year too much.

01:16:02.400 --> 01:16:03.930
And they ask you why.

01:16:03.930 --> 01:16:06.300
And so there's an
auditing process

01:16:06.300 --> 01:16:09.040
of the data that's in here.

01:16:09.040 --> 01:16:12.880
Now the only
downside of it is it

01:16:12.880 --> 01:16:17.810
got big quick when they first
developed it in the 80s.

01:16:17.810 --> 01:16:20.890
And then there was a backlash
from the transit agencies

01:16:20.890 --> 01:16:23.070
in the city saying,
you're asking us

01:16:23.070 --> 01:16:24.250
for too much information.

01:16:24.250 --> 01:16:26.900
This costs too much.

01:16:26.900 --> 01:16:33.610
And so, I don't think they've
added the proper updating of it

01:16:33.610 --> 01:16:39.310
with respect to developments
that have been in the transit

01:16:39.310 --> 01:16:42.270
over the last 10
or 15 years or so.

01:16:45.500 --> 01:16:48.670
And there still is
some inconsistency.

01:16:48.670 --> 01:16:51.260
There's still a
little bit of latitude

01:16:51.260 --> 01:16:54.019
on how you allocate your costs.

01:16:54.019 --> 01:16:55.060
That's the hardest thing.

01:16:55.060 --> 01:16:59.670
And have you guys had
cost allocation models?

01:16:59.670 --> 01:17:00.770
Yeah.

01:17:00.770 --> 01:17:05.810
So you saw the uncertainty
of exactly what you put--

01:17:05.810 --> 01:17:09.530
all these costs-- what
category you put them in.

01:17:09.530 --> 01:17:14.240
And so, that part, while
they define a lot of it,

01:17:14.240 --> 01:17:17.440
they don't define it
down to the bottom.

01:17:17.440 --> 01:17:22.550
And so, I think that there
is, especially in the costs.

01:17:22.550 --> 01:17:25.490
So the cost effectiveness
numbers that come out of

01:17:25.490 --> 01:17:30.180
here aren't necessarily
directly comparable

01:17:30.180 --> 01:17:34.310
depending on the property and
how seriously they take it.

01:17:34.310 --> 01:17:36.890
The other issue
with this is this

01:17:36.890 --> 01:17:39.770
is another thing where
the management style--

01:17:39.770 --> 01:17:42.500
some management actually
ask their people

01:17:42.500 --> 01:17:46.010
to look at other properties
here and report back.

01:17:46.010 --> 01:17:47.490
And they care about it.

01:17:47.490 --> 01:17:50.000
And other management says,
just get that report done.

01:17:50.000 --> 01:17:52.020
Get it out of here.

01:17:52.020 --> 01:17:55.340
So this is a similar thing.

01:17:55.340 --> 01:17:56.660
Leadership is important.

01:18:00.220 --> 01:18:06.360
So this issue of
performance audits.

01:18:06.360 --> 01:18:11.730
So outside of doing it with key
performance indicators going

01:18:11.730 --> 01:18:14.580
to the board, there's
also these efforts

01:18:14.580 --> 01:18:19.950
to do it comprehensively,
maybe a deeper dive, than you

01:18:19.950 --> 01:18:22.470
would do on a regular basis.

01:18:22.470 --> 01:18:25.620
And they usually bring in
outside people consultants

01:18:25.620 --> 01:18:29.520
or maybe a state
group that comes in.

01:18:29.520 --> 01:18:32.130
And they go around,
especially, like, say,

01:18:32.130 --> 01:18:35.700
for the RTAs here in
Massachusetts that are all much

01:18:35.700 --> 01:18:37.500
smaller than the MBTA--

01:18:37.500 --> 01:18:39.480
they have a standardized
performance audit

01:18:39.480 --> 01:18:41.880
group that goes around.

01:18:41.880 --> 01:18:44.700
And they give them information.

01:18:44.700 --> 01:18:47.310
I think the big issue,
especially in the smaller

01:18:47.310 --> 01:18:51.540
properties, is they don't
have the resources to find out

01:18:51.540 --> 01:18:54.840
what other people are doing
very easily as compared

01:18:54.840 --> 01:18:57.482
to the larger cities who
just call up people and say,

01:18:57.482 --> 01:18:58.440
I'm going to come down.

01:18:58.440 --> 01:18:59.820
I want to hear about this.

01:18:59.820 --> 01:19:01.920
Or they set up a
special panel and they

01:19:01.920 --> 01:19:04.840
bring in some experts
on a particular issue.

01:19:04.840 --> 01:19:09.510
What this process allows is
identifying critical issues

01:19:09.510 --> 01:19:14.670
that are performance issues and
then allowing the consultant

01:19:14.670 --> 01:19:16.530
to focus just on
those two or three

01:19:16.530 --> 01:19:20.700
issues or the outside group
and say, give us information

01:19:20.700 --> 01:19:24.600
about how we can improve
just in these areas.

01:19:24.600 --> 01:19:28.920
And then it brings information
from other properties.

01:19:28.920 --> 01:19:32.249
Because these people have
been doing it in other places.

01:19:37.090 --> 01:19:42.020
And the big debate when
this first all started

01:19:42.020 --> 01:19:47.860
and among the people who did
it was, should you focus on

01:19:47.860 --> 01:19:52.840
internally in the trends in your
internal operation or should

01:19:52.840 --> 01:19:55.450
you focus on how you
compare to other people?

01:19:55.450 --> 01:19:59.440
And there's no the answer here.

01:19:59.440 --> 01:20:03.520
I always said, it doesn't
hurt to look at outside.

01:20:03.520 --> 01:20:08.500
But clearly, if you're
looking internally first,

01:20:08.500 --> 01:20:10.900
you can see whether you're
getting better or worse.

01:20:10.900 --> 01:20:13.270
And you know the
data is consistent.

01:20:13.270 --> 01:20:17.500
And you know the issues that
you're having trouble with.

01:20:17.500 --> 01:20:22.730
Because intuitively, you know
it as well as from the data.

01:20:22.730 --> 01:20:30.880
So I would say, generally,
the peer comparisons were

01:20:30.880 --> 01:20:34.540
often used by the outside
groups to say, where should we

01:20:34.540 --> 01:20:36.730
focus going in?

01:20:36.730 --> 01:20:39.470
And let's dig deeper
in these areas,

01:20:39.470 --> 01:20:43.615
because these numbers look
a little bit out of context.

01:20:46.670 --> 01:20:47.820
Almost done here.

01:20:47.820 --> 01:20:51.530
So I'm going to press on for--

01:20:51.530 --> 01:20:53.480
to--

01:20:53.480 --> 01:20:57.440
So the bulk of the
effort was internally.

01:20:57.440 --> 01:21:00.020
One thing that this
allows is because you

01:21:00.020 --> 01:21:02.930
have this facilitator
and the outside group,

01:21:02.930 --> 01:21:08.710
it allows you to tell
them, like a counselor,

01:21:08.710 --> 01:21:11.380
this is why I really
can't get my job done.

01:21:11.380 --> 01:21:17.880
And we really developed
a mode with these folks.

01:21:17.880 --> 01:21:18.780
You can tell us.

01:21:18.780 --> 01:21:20.880
We're not going to
attribute it to you.

01:21:20.880 --> 01:21:23.610
We're not going to necessarily
go to your direct boss

01:21:23.610 --> 01:21:25.560
about your complaint
to the direct boss.

01:21:25.560 --> 01:21:27.720
But we might mention
this to somebody

01:21:27.720 --> 01:21:31.150
higher up in a more general way.

01:21:31.150 --> 01:21:33.660
And we had ways
of assuring them.

01:21:33.660 --> 01:21:37.260
And so, employees
liked this, especially

01:21:37.260 --> 01:21:41.970
if they were hitting roadblocks
in doing a better job.

01:21:41.970 --> 01:21:44.970
And in small properties,
sometimes personalities

01:21:44.970 --> 01:21:46.810
got in the way.

01:21:46.810 --> 01:21:49.930
And so we would provide that
feedback to the top management

01:21:49.930 --> 01:21:51.370
as long as they wanted it.

01:21:54.100 --> 01:21:58.960
And just I'm aware of a
very significant state

01:21:58.960 --> 01:22:00.640
program in California.

01:22:00.640 --> 01:22:04.600
They have to do this
every three years.

01:22:04.600 --> 01:22:05.620
It started at two.

01:22:05.620 --> 01:22:07.210
Now it's down to three.

01:22:07.210 --> 01:22:08.830
And they have a set format.

01:22:08.830 --> 01:22:13.390
And they send the same kind
of people around to each one.

01:22:13.390 --> 01:22:18.790
And there's some compliance
with state requirements

01:22:18.790 --> 01:22:21.280
and funding and
things like that.

01:22:21.280 --> 01:22:24.460
But it really was
a comprehensive.

01:22:24.460 --> 01:22:27.770
And they looked in
these five focus areas.

01:22:27.770 --> 01:22:31.960
And they essentially--
when you got the feedback

01:22:31.960 --> 01:22:34.450
from most of the smaller
properties, at least,

01:22:34.450 --> 01:22:36.340
they felt like this
was a great program.

01:22:36.340 --> 01:22:41.770
Because it gave them the
ability to focus harder

01:22:41.770 --> 01:22:45.230
on things on a periodic basis.

01:22:45.230 --> 01:22:48.790
And then when you came back, you
measured those areas and said,

01:22:48.790 --> 01:22:54.810
OK, what else was
going on at that point?

01:22:54.810 --> 01:22:56.500
I think that's where
I'm going to stop.

01:22:56.500 --> 01:22:58.330
Yeah.

01:22:58.330 --> 01:23:00.730
Anybody have any last questions?

01:23:00.730 --> 01:23:04.581
We can pick this up a little
bit in the service contracting

01:23:04.581 --> 01:23:05.080
stuff.

01:23:05.080 --> 01:23:07.240
Because it comes up there, too.

01:23:07.240 --> 01:23:10.420
The difference
between performance

01:23:10.420 --> 01:23:15.160
in your internal operations and
performance by your contractors

01:23:15.160 --> 01:23:17.080
is nothing.

01:23:17.080 --> 01:23:21.280
In fact, it's harder to
manage the service contract.

01:23:21.280 --> 01:23:25.510
And we can talk about
that at the next one.

01:23:25.510 --> 01:23:27.156
OK.

01:23:27.156 --> 01:23:28.840
Anybody?

01:23:28.840 --> 01:23:29.440
Great.

01:23:29.440 --> 01:23:30.990
Thanks.

